<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Seizes 165 Kilograms of Hashish </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, November 24 (Xinhua) -- Turkish police and gendarme
soldiers seized 165 kilograms of hashish in a recent operation in
eastern Turkey, the semi-official Anatolia News Agency reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The agency quoted a statement issued by the office of Bitlis
governor as saying that the gendarme soldiers disguised as drug
buyers bargained with drug smuggler Felemez Aslan in Mutki town of
Bitlis province. However, Aslan found the drug buyers as
government troops and managed to flee in the dark.
</P>
<P>
The government troops searched some places in the town and
found the 165 kilograms of hashish in 10 bags, said the
statement. But it failed to give the date when the drug was
seized.
</P>
<P>
The gendarme soldiers had staged operations in search of
Felemez Aslan in the region, according to the statement.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the Turkish police seized 4.4 tonnes of heroin,
accounting for 40 percent of the world's total haul, 12.3 tonnes
of hashish, 233 kilograms of opium, 13 kilograms of cocaine and
1,157 kilograms of base morphine. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
