<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading U.S. Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
-- The White House and some members of Congress are seeking ways to
provide health insurance for 3 million Americans aged 55 to 64 years
old who are too young for Medicared and not poor enough for Medicaid.
Many have chronic illneses that require extensive and costly care.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post
</P>
<P>
-- Iraq's ambassador to the United Nations, Nizar Hamdoon, said
yesterday his government still does not recognize the right of U.N.
inspection teams to enter certain sites inside Iraq, provoking
senior U.S. officials to say that the dispute between Iraq and the
international organization has not ended.
</P>
<P>
--In the first half of 1997, murders and robberies were down 9
percent from last year, the FBI said.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal
</P>
<P>
-- Reno is expected to reject an independent-counsel inquiry into
telephone fund-raising by Clinton and Gore, senior officials, who
requested anonymity, said Saturday. Aides have recommended the
attorney general not seek a Clinton-Gore inquiry or a counsel to probe
if former Energy Secretary O'Leary solicited an illegal contribution.
</P>
<P>
-- Affirmative-action laws remain unsettled after civil-rights
groups agreed to contribute more than 300,000 dollars to settle a
white New jersey school teacher's complaint last week. The U.S.
Supreme Court had been set to hear the case and experts say no other
case is likely to be taken up by the court soon in its place.
</P>
<P>
USA Today
</P>
<P>
-- Many big cities won't be able to supply enough jobs or support
services to put welfare recipients to work, mayors group says.
</P>
