<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Pledges to Tackle International Terrorism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, November 24 (Xinhua) -- British Home Secretary Jack
Straw today promised to strengthen his efforts in cracking down on
terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Responding to accusations by Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
that Britain was harboring terrorists, Straw said, "Tackling
international terrorism is a top priority for this government."
</P>
<P>
"We already have tough anti-terrorism laws and we intend to
strengthen these further," he said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak on Sunday criticized some countries, including Britain,
for sheltering fugitive Muslim militants and said they encouraged
attacks such as last week's massacre in Luxor of 58 foreign
tourists.
</P>
<P>
However, Straw's Home Office (interior ministry) has denied
Britain granted asylum to convicted terrorists, saying asylum was
only ever granted on the grounds established under the United
Nations' 1951 convention on refugees.
</P>
<P>
Straw last month pledged to overhaul Britain's anti-terrorism
laws, which currently do not make plotting to commit guerrilla
attacks abroad an offense.
</P>
<P>
Britain has come under attack in recent years from Tunisia,
Saudi Arabia and Israel, which have accused it of sheltering
guerrillas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
