<DOCNO> XIE19971125.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Namibian President to Visit S. Africa Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, November 24 (Xinhua) -- South African President
Nelson Mandela will hold talks with his Namibian counterpart Sam
Nujoma in Cape Town on Wednesday, a presidential spokesman Parks
Mankahlana said today.
</P>
<P>
Mandela and Nujoma will discuss matters of common interest,
including bilateral and regional issues, Mankahlana said.
</P>
<P>
There is a general realization among Southern African
Development Community (SADC) member states of the need for
greater cooperation between governments, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Mandela currently chairs the SADC.
</P>
<P>
Namibia, along with other SADC members such as Zimbabwe, is
critical of South Africa's economic dominance in the region and
has accused it of being too protectionist.
</P>
<P>
In August, Namibia accused South Africa of having designed
measures to hamper industrial development in the Southern African
Custom Union area in order to protect South African industries.
</P>
<P>
Namibia is also critical of South Africa's attempt to
negotiate a preferential trade agreement with the European Union,
which it fears, may be detrimental to its interests and those of
other SADC member states.
</P>
<P>
Another thorny issue is the disagreement between Mandela and
Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe on who should chair the SADC
organ on politics, defense and security, which came to a head at
the recent SADC heads of state summit in Malawi. 
</P>
</TEXT>
