<HEADLINE> Drug Cartels Have Become World Threat: Zimbabwean </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, November 24 (Xinhua) -- The global influence of drug
cartels has become a threat to the socio-economic and political
order of countries in the world, Zimbabwe's Home Affairs Minister
Dumiso Dabengwa said today.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks at a five-day Southern African Development
Community (SADC) workshop on illicit drug trafficking held in
Nyanga in east Zimbabwe. He said that the activities of drug
cartels could threaten the ability of governments to assert their
authority and to maintain order in their countries.
</P>
<P>
"The people involved in the illicit drug trade and the
organized crime groups have little respect for our laws and for
the lives of our people," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said drug cartels are motivated by financial greed and they
had grown through bribing the weak and corrupting the innocent.
</P>
<P>
"Drug trafficking and abuse are beginning to pose serious
problems in Zimbabwe and in most of the SADC countries," the
minister said.
</P>
<P>
The workshop is being attended by participants from the SADC
region.
</P>
<P>
Dabengwa stressed the need for the countries in the region to
tighten their boundaries and take other effective steps to
curb drug trafficking and abuses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
