<DOCNO> XIE19971125.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepal Stresses Need for New Treaty With India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, November 24 (Xinhua) -- Nepali Foreign Minister
Kamal Thapa today once again stressed the need for a new treaty
with India to replace the 1950 Indo-Nepal treaty, the official RSS
news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Thapa raised the issue when addressing a
briefing-and-orientation program organized by the Institute of
Foreign Affairs for some Nepalese ambassadors.
</P>
<P>
During a visit to India in mid-September, Thapa had officially
proposed to New Delhi that the Peace and Friendship Treaty be
replaced with a new one.
</P>
<P>
Thapa told the ambassadors that Kalapani in far-western Nepal
belongs to Nepal and the Indian army should be withdrawn from
there. Talks are underway with India on the issue, and if the
demand is vindicated, India will leave Kalapani, he said.
</P>
<P>
On the issue of Bhutanese refugees, Thapa said his government
aims to solve the problem by fostering relations with Bhutan on
the basis of goodwill, confidence and mutual understanding.
</P>
<P>
Nepal will not internationalize the issue, but ambassadors
should regularly inform the countries where they are posted about
the developments in this connection, he said.
</P>
<P>
About 100,000 Bhutanese refugees have been staying in eastern
Nepal in eight U.N.-run camps after being forced to flee Bhutan in
1989 and the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
Thapa also stressed that the economic diplomacy being pursued
by Nepal should give priority to trade, foreign investment and
tourism.
</P>
<P>
Thapa was named foreign minister in mid-June and retained the
post after the government led by Surya Bahadur Thapa took office
in early October.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
