<DOCNO> XIE19971125.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Anti-AIDS Campaign Launched in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, November 24 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe today joined the
world nations in launching the anti-AIDS campaign as the
incidence of HIV/AIDS escalates, especially among young people.
</P>
<P>
The campaign was launched under the theme "children living in
a world with AIDS" in an effort to highlight the plight of
children who have become vulnerable due to increased cases of
child abuse.
</P>
<P>
Officially launching the campaign here, Zimbabwe's first lady
Grace Mugabe challenged every Zimbabwean to make a firm
commitment to curbing the spread of the pandemic.
</P>
<P>
She said the number of orphans who were losing their parents
to AIDS and ended up looking after themselves were on the
increase as most relatives could not take care of them.
</P>
<P>
"I appeal to all Zimbabweans to unite in condemning,
confronting and stamping out the evil of HIV positive
perpetrators who traumatize children and cut short their lives,"
she said.
</P>
<P>
"Appropriate behavior based on good old morality and
self-respect is the surest and cheapest long term solution to the
problem of AIDS," said Mugabe.
</P>
<P>
Health and Child Welfare Minister Timothy Stamps called on
parents to speak frankly about the dangers of HIV/AIDS to their
children.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe has one of the highest number of HIV infected people
in Africa. Of Zimbabwe's 12.4 million people, it is estimated
that most of the 10 percent infected with the HIV virus that
causes AIDS are those in the productive age group.
</P>
<P>
Statistics shows that there is an increasing number of
reported AIDS cases among the 15 to 19 years age group, with
girls constituting about 80 percent of HIV infections in this age
group. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
