<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-24 17:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Ambassador Urges Global Efforts to Eradicate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, November 12 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Ambassador to Egypt Edward
Walker today called for concerting international efforts to
eradicate terrorist activities.
</P>
<P>
Walker issued the call after his meeting with Arab League
Secretary General Esmat Abdul Meguid on the occasion of the end of
his four-year term as ambassador to Egypt.
</P>
<P>
He said that his talks with Meguid tackled the threats of
terrorism, citing the recent massacre in southern Egypt.
</P>
<P>
Islamic militants killed 58 foreign tourists and four Egyptians
before they were gunned down by the security police in front of an
ancient temple in Luxor, about 500 kilometers south of Cairo, on
November 17.
</P>
<P>
Walker said joint efforts can be exerted to stem that kind of
activity as it is a common enemy to Egypt, the United States and
all the countries in the region.
</P>
<P>
Walker said he also discussed with Meguid the current
developments in the region, especially those related to the peace
process, but they did not deal in detail with the latest
developments in the Iraq-U.N. crisis.
</P>
<P>
However, he said both of them agreed that diplomacy played a
key role in handling the crisis and setting matters on the right
course.
</P>
<P>
Walker, who represented the U.S. in the United Nations and in
the United Arab Emirates during the 1991 Gulf War, will become
U.S. ambassador to Israel if confirmed by the Congress.
</P>
<P>
The ambassadorial reshuffle comes after Martin Indyk, the
former U.S. ambassador to Israel, took the position of assistant
secretary of state for Near East affairs, leaving the crucial
ambassadorial position vacant during a period of increasingly
strained relations between Israel and the U.S..
</P>
<P>
Walker, a proponent of the privatization of Egypt's state-owned
companies, is being hailed by the Egyptian government and members
of the private sector as one of Egypt's most successful foreign
ambassadors because of his involvement in bringing U.S. companies
to invest in Egypt's markets.
</P>
<P>
Daniel Kurtzer, a Jew, was nominated as U.S. new ambassador to
Egypt.
</P>
<P>
Kurtzer has been a foreign service officer for 21 years,
including two years in the U.S. Embassy in Cairo, and served as
secretary for political affairs at the American Embassy in Tel
Aviv. 
</P>
</TEXT>
