<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-24 17:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cypriot Government to Accept UN Procedure: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, November 24 (Xinhua) -- The Cypriot government will
accept any procedure the U.N. considers proper for a settlement
to the Cyprus problem, a government spokesman said here today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at his daily press briefing, government spokesman
Manolis Christofides said the methodology and procedure followed
during the peace talks between the two Cypriot communities in the
U.S. and Switzerland in July and August had been chosen by the
U.N. Secretary-General and "it's not for us to say if they were
wrong."
</P>
<P>
The spokesman was commenting on statements made at a press
conference in Nicosia last Friday by U.N. Secretary-General's
Special Advisor on Cyprus Diego Cordovez that the methodology he
had used in the summer peace talks was wrong.
</P>
<P>
Cordovez chaired the two rounds of direct talks between
Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides and Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf
Denktash in July and August, but the talks produced no results.
</P>
<P>
"It is not the methodology that is to blame, but the lack of
goodwill and the intransigence the Turkish side continues to
show in every round of peace talks," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
What is important today, he added, is that the U.N. is
planning to begin new and decisive negotiations immediately after
the Cyprus's presidential elections in February 1998.
</P>
<P>
"We are prepared to follow the procedure which the U.N. will
propose," Christofides said, adding that the Cypriot government
is willing to participate in any talks and negotiations for a
Cyprus settlement.
</P>
<P>
Cordovez, who visited the island last week for the first time
since he was appointed special envoy earlier this year, has
warned that international interest in a Cyprus settlement will
end if a solution can not be found during next year's renewed
effort.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on this, Christofides said the international
interest should concentrate on the implementation of
U.N. resolutions on Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
"If this is the wish of the U.N. and influential governments,
the Cyprus resolutions can be implemented," he added.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into Greek Cypriot South and Turkish
Cypriot North since 1974 when Turkish troops landed and took
over the northern third of the island in the wake of a failed
pro-Athens coup in Nicosia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
