<HEADLINE> French FM: No EU Letter Blasting Netanyahu </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, November 24 (Xinhua) -- Visiting French Foreign
Minister Hubert Vedrine denied here today that he is bringing a
letter from the European Union (EU) assailing Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu for torpedoing the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a joint news conference after his meeting with his
Israeli counterpart David Levy, Vedrine said that "there is not
a letter like that and I don't know from where the information
about the letter was got."
</P>
<P>
But he said that the EU, like the United States and other
friendly countries of Israel, is worried about the deadlocked
peace talks, noting that the only way to achieve stability and
security in the Middle East is to advance the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Local media Sunday quoted diplomatic sources as saying that
Vedrine will convey a verbal message from the EU to Jerusalem,
which urges Israel to move forward the peace process and
attributes the current stalemate to Netanyahu's policies.
</P>
<P>
The sources also said that there is a consensus between
Britain, France, and Germany on this issue and British Prime
Minister Tony Blair had spelled it out to Netanyahu at their
meeting on November 13 in London.
</P>
<P>
Levy told reporters that during their meeting he briefed
Vedrine on the latest development in the Israeli-Palestinian
peace talks. He praised France for its efforts to push forward
the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Levy said that "although the peace process is difficult, there
is no alternative for it."
</P>
<P>
He stressed that Israel wants to resume peace talks with
Syria, noting that real efforts should be made to break the
deadlock in Israeli-Syrian talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
