<HEADLINE> Indian Coaches Serve Tanzanian Passengers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, November 24 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian Railways
Corporation has received 12 out of 27 third class coaches ordered
from India, boosting its passenger service, particularly on its
central line between Dar es Salaam, Mwanza and Kigoma, local
newspaper the East African reported today.
</P>
<P>
A senior TRC official said the 12 coaches were delivered last
month and the rest are expected to arrive shortly.
</P>
<P>
The newly received coaches will bring the number of TRC's
serviceable coaches to 61, alleviating the hardship passengers
have been facing in catching trains to the capital and other
urban centers.
</P>
<P>
The coach shortage had been worsened by a TRC requirement
which outlawed standing passengers on any of its train services.
The corporation runs regular passenger services on the Dar es
Salaam-Tabora main line which branches off at Tabora to Mwanza on
Lake Victoria and to Kigoma on Lake Tanganyika.
</P>
<P>
Stiff competition from bus companies has shut out the
corporation's shuttle service on the Dar es Salaam-Moshi and Dar
es Salaam-Tanga lines. The additional coaches, say TRC officials,
may not greatly change the situation, but it will improve the
company's ability to compete with the bus companies.
</P>
<P>
The delivery of the coaches come eight months after the
corporation received 67 fuel tank wagons under a European Union
grant which also included the offer of the coaches. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
