<HEADLINE> African Women Urged to Enhance Role in Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, November 24 (Xinhua) -- African women today were
urged to unite and enhance their role in conflict resolution and
peace building activities of the continent.
</P>
<P>
The call was made by Ugandan Vice-President Specioza W.
Kazibwe in her keynote address at the opening session of a
three-day workshop on documented best practices of women in peace
building and non violent means of conflict resolution held here.
</P>
<P>
Kazibwe stressed the need for the establishment of a strong
institutional framework whereby women could come together and
intensify their struggle against all sorts of violence affecting
themselves and the general public.
</P>
<P>
Women's initiatives during the process of peace building,
conflict prevention and resolution could not bring fruitful
achievements unless backed by pertinent governmental as well as
international bodies, she said.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the session, Ethiopian Education Minister Genet
Zewdi stressed the importance of empowerment of African women,
saying that women's access to decision making activities is the best
approach to conflict resolution and peace building progresses
both at the grass-roots and community levels.
</P>
<P>
She said conflict and violence usually surface in areas where
women's right to decision making activities are violated or not
at all ensured.
</P>
<P>
Women activities drawn from Burundi, Congo, Liberia, Mali,
Rwanda, Sudan, Somali and Ethiopia as well as representatives of
government and inter-government organizations and United Nations
agencies are attending the three-day workshop. 
</P>
</TEXT>
