<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-24 18:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Denies US Allegation of Obstructing UN's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, November 24 (Xinhua) -- Iraq today denied U.S. Defense
Secretary William Cohen's allegation that Iraqi authorities had
obstructed U.N. inspectors' access to suspected sites in Iraq, the
official Iraqi News Agency (INA) reported.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted an official spokesman as saying that Cohen's
statement was meant to mislead the world public opinion in
preparation for straining Iraq's relationship with the
U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM) in charge of dismantling Iraqi
weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
According to the INA report, the places to which U.N. weapons
inspection teams were denied access were three Saddam Hussein's
presidential buildings.
</P>
<P>
On September 27, a U.N. inspection team demanded access to a
Special Republican Military unit through a special path which did
not lead to the unit, but to a presidential building, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
During the incident, the team head was offered to be taken to
that unit through another path, but he refused and decided to
withdraw.
</P>
<P>
As a U.N. inspection team demanded access to one of the
presidential sites on September 29, a high-level Iraqi official
asked the team head to enter with him into the site. In case the
inspector find anything related to weapons of mass destruction, a
group of the team would be called in.
</P>
<P>
However, the head decided to withdraw his team under the
pretext of bad contacts with New York, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The third incident occurred on October 1 when a
U.N. inspection team demanded access to a dilapidated building at
another presidential site, which the team thought was one of the
security departments.
</P>
<P>
In that incident, a senior Iraqi official offered to accompany
the team head into that building, but the inspector refused and
decided to withdraw, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The INA report quoted the spokesman as saying that the Iraqi
side did not practically deny U.N. access to those sites, rather
it offered alternatives that were rejected by the inspectors
themselves.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that what had been mentioned above was a
cogent evidence "on the campaign of lies and facts distortion
launched by the United States against Iraq." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
