<DOCNO> XIE19971125.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Continues to Dominate Global Drugs Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, November 24 (Xinhua) -- The global drugs market
continued to be dominated by the U.S. market in September, with
U.S. year-on-year growth rising to 15 percent compared with a
seven percent average growth of the world's 10 largest markets.
</P>
<P>
Citing figures released today by IMS International, a
specialist provider of healthcare information, the Financial Times
newspaper reported today that pharmaceuticals sales in 10 of the
largest national markets rose to 167.4 billion U.S. dollars for
the year to September.
</P>
<P>
The growth was led by the U.S. market which edged up from 14
percent in the year to August to 15 percent in September at 66
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
However, sales in the second and third biggest markets in Japan
and Germany were stagnant, with sales standing at 43.4 billion
dollars and 14.9 billion dollars respectively.
</P>
<P>
Growth was also slow in France with an increase of three
percent to 14.1 billion dollars. Italy grew at seven percent to
8.8 billion, the UK at eight percent to 7.5 billion, Spain eight
percent to 4.9 billion dollars and Canada eight percent to 4.0
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that by medical area, nervous systems drugs
made the strongest growth with a 14 percent sales growth to 23
billion dollars while sales of heart drugs, digestive system drugs
and anti-infective drugs all increased by seven percent to 34
billion, 27.4 billion and 17.6 billion respectively.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
