<HEADLINE> Israeli Warplanes Attack Guerrillas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, November 24 (Xinhua) -- Israeli warplanes and
artilleries today pounded south Lebanon and the country's eastern
area of Bekka Valley as a response to guerrillas' attacks on its
outposts.
</P>
<P>
The fighting has lasted for two days since Saturday midnight
when Lebanese guerrillas fired shells on the village of Beit Lif
in the western sector of the Israeli-occupied south Lebanon,
claiming lives of nine Lebanese civilians and leaving 12 others
wounded.
</P>
<P>
At 12:20 (GMT 10:20), Israeli warplanes fired air-to-surface
missiles in the areas surrounding the village of Hania, near
the Israeli border, in which Nepalese troops base of the
United Nations Interim Force in Lebanon(UNIFIL) is located.
</P>
<P>
After less than one hour, Israeli planes blasted the areas
surrounding the villages of Majdail Zun, 99 kilometers south of
Beirut, which were believed to be often used by guerrillas as a
launching pad for operations against Israeli troops. But no
casualties were caused.
</P>
<P>
In addition to air raids, Israeli artillery also bombarded the
villages in the western part, which faces an Israeli-occupied
enclave in the south.
</P>
<P>
Guerrillas used rocket-propelled grenades, mortars and
automatic weapons to respond Israel's strike. The statement issued
by guerrillas said that they "scored direct hits" in the enemy's
positions.
</P>
<P>
Muslim guerrillas are fighting a war to dislodge Israeli and
its ally troops from the 1,200-square-kilometer area in southern
Lebanon they have occupied since 1985 with an aim to prevent
cross-border guerrilla attack upon north Israel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
