<HEADLINE> Cameroon's Oppositlion NUDP Expresses Willingness </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The chairman of the National Union for Democracy and
Progress (NUDP) made the remarks in an exclusive interview with CRTV
here this morning after the NUDP central committee ended two-day
meeting over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
"It is our firm believe that in a democratic civilized country,
contact, dialogue between the government or the party in power and
the oppositions are normal things, provided they are done openly
through normal channels," he said.
</P>
<P>
Bello Bouba declared that neither he nor any member in the
hierarchy of his party has so far been contacted by the ruling
Cameroon People's Democratic Movement (CPDM) to join a possible
coalition government in the aftermath of the recent presidential
elections.
</P>
<P>
Bello's remarks came in the wake of speculations that there
were advanced negotiations between the CPDM represented by Amadou Ali,
the Secretary General at the presidency and the NUDP for the latter to
join a coalition government.
</P>
<P>
The NUDP leader nevertherless admitted to have met with Amadou Ali
at least once since the presidential inauguration, "but on a purely
personal basis."
</P>
<P>
If the NUDP is officially contacted by the CPDM, Bello Bouba
said, the response of his party will depend on the terms of what
would be proposed.
</P>
<P>
The NUDP whose leader came third in the 1992 presidential elections
after Paul Biya of CPDM, Fru Ndi of SDF, last October joined the
Social Democratic Movement (SDF) and the Cameroon Democratic Union
(CDU) to boycott the country's second multiparty presidential poll.
</P>
</TEXT>
