<HEADLINE> ECOWAS, Sierra Leone Junta to Open 2nd-Phase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, November 24 (Xinhua) -- The second phase of negotiation
on restoring the ousted civilian government in Sierra Leone is
expected to open soon, a senior sub-regional organization
official said here today.
</P>
<P>
Lansana Kouyate, Executive Secretary of the Economic Community
of West African States (ECOWAS), disclosed he would leave for
Freetown, Sierra Leone today to make preparations for the talks.
</P>
<P>
He said he was mandated by the ECOWAS Committee of Five on
Sierra Leone to do so and will report to the committee when he
comes back so that it can assess the situation in that country.
</P>
<P>
Normally, the negotiation will be held on November 28, said
Kouyate, a Guinean diplomat who took the post at the ECOWAS
summit last August.
</P>
<P>
The committee of five and the ruling junta in Freetown, which
seized power in the May 25 coup, had their first round talks last
month in Conakry, Guinea.
</P>
<P>
At the end of the meeting, the junta agreed to step down and
hand over to the ousted government led by President Ahmed Tejan
Kabbah in April next year.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, the junta leader, Major Johnny Paul
Koroma, and the commander of the west African peacekeeping force
(ECOMOG), Major-General Victor Malu, met in Freetown to work out
modalities for the implementation of the Conakry peace accord.
</P>
<P>
But they failed to reach consensus as to whether the armed
forces of Sierra Leone should be disarmed, among other key
issues.
</P>
<P>
As peace and security are so crucial for the development of
the west African sub-region, one of the poorest region in the
world, the ECOWAS has expressed strong determination to solve the
Sierra Leone crisis, particularly after it has successfully
helped bring an end to the seven-year-old civil war in Liberia.
</P>
<P>
In this concern, "much has to be done before April next year,"
said the new ECOWAS executive secretary. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
