<DOCNO> XIE19971125.0043 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-24 19:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rafsanjani Urges Formation of Political Parties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, November 24 (Xinhua) -- Chairman of Iran's State
Expediency Council (SEC) and former President Akbar Hashemi
Rafsanjani today urged the formation of political parties in the
country.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the Iranian official news agency IRNA, Rafsanjani
attributed the recent political developments concerning the power
of the country's supreme leader to the absence of political
parties in the country.
</P>
<P>
Rafsanjani was referring to the event that earlier this month,
a famous Iranian religious canonist, Ayatollah Hussein Ali
Mentazeri, accused Supreme Leader Ayatollah Seyed Ali Khamenei of
intervening in the government's affairs.
</P>
<P>
The remarks by Mentazeri triggered series of condemnation and
attacks from religious and political figures and organizations.
</P>
<P>
Rafsanjani pointed out that democracy in parallel with
existence of political parties is legally allowed in Iran.
</P>
<P>
"If a variety of political parties were not formed, democracy
would not take shape in Iran and we would have similar events in
future," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that groups have replaced the political parties, the
people belonging to these groups make statements but they do not
regard themselves responsible.
</P>
<P>
In 1981, late Iranian leader Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini issued
an order to dismantle political parties. There have been only
political factions and groups in the country since then.
</P>
<P>
Rafsanjani said the recent events over the issue of the
supreme leadership, Velayat-e Faqih (governance of supreme
religious jurisprudent), were launched by "the dirty hands of the
enemies and something which has its roots in miscalculations."
</P>
<P>
However, he stressed that exchange of views should be carried
out in a healthy atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
Rafsanjani also denied any interference by the SEC in the
affairs of the executive and legislative branches of the
government.
</P>
<P>
According to the country's constitution, he said, the SEC
arbitrates on any dispute between the Majlis (parliament) and the
Guardians Council and provides the supreme leader with
consultations, adding that the SEC is far from any factional
tendency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
