<HEADLINE> European Shares Fall on Yamaichi's Collapse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, November 24 (Xinhua) -- Major European Stock indices
suffered heavy losses Monday and all ended sharply lower as news
of the collapse of Japan's fourth biggest brokerage Yamaichi
Securities shook world markets.
</P>
<P>
The FTSE 100 index in London had fallen to a low of 4,883.6
earlier today in thin trading after the Yamaichi collapse sparked
fears of a deeper fallout in Japan.
</P>
<P>
However, the market cut some of its losses later in the day and
ended down 87.2 points at 4,898.6.
</P>
<P>
Asia-sensitive stocks, such as HSBC and Standard Chartered, led
the sell-off in the London market.
</P>
<P>
German shares in Frankfurt closed 3.3 percent lower although
dealers said shares had recovered from session lows.
</P>
<P>
The market also turned its focus to the collapse of Yamaichi
and worries about the impact across international bourses. The
DAX-30 index finished at 3,830.63, down 129.06 points.
</P>
<P>
The CAC-40 index in Paris ended 59.22 points lower at 2,802.48.
Traders said that the bourse was cautious as investors watched
developments in Asian financial markets. 
