<HEADLINE> Inter-Africa Coffee Organization's Assembly Opens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, November 24 (Xinhua) -- An annual assembly of the
Inter-Africa Coffee Organization opened here today to discuss
1997-98 quotas and seek ways to increase coffee production by
disease and pest control.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the opening session of the 37th assembly, Ugandan
President Yoweri Museveni called on African coffee producing
countries to address the massive loss of coffee value to
foreigners, saying this fundamental question has to be addressed
as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
The president noted that while one hundred grams of instant
coffee in developed countries costs about seven Dollars, African
coffee producers are getting about three Dollars for a kilogram
of unprocessed coffee.
</P>
<P>
He urged coffee producing countries to enhance research
networks to ensure increased productivity through disease and
pest control as well as development of high yielding breeds.
</P>
<P>
At the three-day conference, the participants will discuss
their 1997-98 quotas and examine the coffee wilt disease
situation in Africa.
</P>
<P>
Attending the meeting were ministers and experts from African
coffee producing countries and representatives of the
International Coffee Organization. 
</P>
