<HEADLINE> French President Defends Idea of European Manned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, November 24 (Xinhua) -- French President Jacques Chirac
today defended the idea to develop manned space flight by European
countries which he said should be let Europe catch up with the
United States as a great power in space.
</P>
<P>
"The mastering of (rocket) launchers and the manned flights
are guarantee of the status of great power" for Europe, said
Chirac during a visit to the European space center in Kourou,
French Guyana, where the Ariane space rockets are launched.
</P>
<P>
"Man in space is also the confirmation of our presence," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Chirac praised French astronaut Jean-Loup Chretien who has
joined American space flights but has been criticized at home for
supporting American space programs.
</P>
<P>
Among his critics is the Minister of National Education,
Technology and Research, Claude Allegre, who disapproves of manned
space flight.
</P>
<P>
Chirac said that Europe is cooperating with the United States,
Canada and Japan to develop a kind of spacecraft which is smaller
than the American space shuttles but capable of carrying
astronauts to space stations and bringing them back home. 
</P>
</TEXT>
