<HEADLINE> German Officials Differ on Jobless Outlook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, November 24 (Xinhua) -- Germany's federal labour office
president, Bernhard Jagoda, said today that it is still premature
to predict that the country's joblessness would surge to a new
record of five million this winter.
</P>
<P>
His remarks came after Economic Minister Guenter Rexrodt said
over the weekend that it could not be ruled out the jobless total
might reach the five-million mark occasionally.
</P>
<P>
Jagoda, however, argued that he did not expected any major
seasonal job cuts in the construction sector this winter because
of the introduction of new wage arrangements in that sector since
November 1.
</P>
<P>
In order to combat the country's already high unemployment,
which was 4.29 million in October, Jagoda repeated his call for
tax and pension reforms.
</P>
<P>
But what is also necessary are flexible working hour
regulations, more domestic investment and more innovation, he
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
