<HEADLINE> Sudanese Opposition Leader Arrives in Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, November 24 (Xinhua) -- John Garang, leader of Sudan's
largest rebel group, arrived here today for talks with Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak on the latest developments in Sudan.
</P>
<P>
Addressing reporters upon his arrival, Garang said his meeting
with Mubarak is meant to expound the peace efforts by his Sudan
People's Liberation Army (SPLA).
</P>
<P>
Garang, on his first visit to Cairo, welcomed Egypt's handling
and assessment of the situation in Sudan, and its support for
peace efforts in Sudan.
</P>
<P>
He said that his Cairo trip is a good opportunity to reassure
his determination to establish peace and democracy in Sudan and to
protect the national and territorial integrity of Sudan.
</P>
<P>
Garang's visit came less than a month after Sudanese Vice
President el-Zubeir Mohammed Salih met with Mubarak here in a bid
to improve the strained ties between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Relations between Cairo and Khartoum virtually went chilled
after Egypt accused Sudan of involving in a 1995 assassination
attempt on Mubarak in Addis Ababa, Ethiopia. However, Sudan denied
the charge.
</P>
<P>
The two neighbors also have disputes over the control of the
Halaib border region on the Red Sea.
</P>
<P>
The Garang-led rebel group has been fighting the Islamic
government since 1983 to press for more independence for the
southern third of Sudan. So far, it refused to sign peace treaty
with the government.
</P>
<P>
Over 1 million people have died either in the fighting or
famine in this African country during the 14-year-old civil war in
southern Sudan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
