<HEADLINE> US, DPRK to Hold Talks in Washington </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 24 (Xinhua) -- Officials of both the
United States and the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK)
will hold bilateral talks in Washington this week, the State
Department said today.
</P>
<P>
The talks will be held at the vice foreign ministers' level and
will cover "a range of issues," State Department spokesman James
Foley told reporters.
</P>
<P>
U.S. officials said it was likely that Charles Kartman, U.S.
deputy assistant secretary of state, will lead the U.S. delegation
while Vice Foreign Minister Kim Gye-gwan will be the head of the
DPRK delegation.
</P>
<P>
The two men were also the heads of their delegations to talks
in New York last week, which reached an agreement that the DPRK,
South Korea, the United States and China will convene a meeting in
Geneva on December 9 to discuss peace issues on the Korean
Peninsula. That is the so-called four-party talks.
</P>
<P>
The officials said issues on the agenda will likely be a
planned exchange of liaison offices and search for remains of
Americans missing from the Korean War.
</P>
<P>
It is the first time that DPRK officials at the vice foreign
minister level hold talks with their counterparts at the State
Department in Washington D.C. The two countries usually talked in
New York as they had no diplomatic relations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
