<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Recommends to Create New UN Haitian Mission </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, November 24 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan today recommended to create a new UN Haitian mission to
replace the United Nations Transition Mission in Haiti(UNTMIH)
which was established in August 1997 and would expire on November
30, 1997.
</P>
<P>
In his report to the Security Council, Annan said the new
mission, known as the United Nations Police Mission in Haiti
(MIPONUH) with a mandate period of six months, would be composed
of up to 290 police officers, including a 90-strong special unit.
The police personnel would continue to carry personal weapons.
</P>
<P>
Annan said the proposed mission would have its headquarters in
Port-au Prince. It would oversee the technical assistance to the
Haitian National Police founded by the United Nations Development
Program (UNDP) and would operate closely with other
international and regional organizations in the country.
</P>
<P>
The UN chief said while the Haitian National Police has made
substantial progress forward, its development into a professional
force continued to be slow and uneven. The Young police force
continued to have difficulty in dealing effectively with the
country's increasing security demands.
</P>
<P>
The Secretary-General said the Haitian National Police would
continue to need international support during the legislative
election to be held in November 1998, and the proposed mission
would allow for continued international support through the
critical election period.
</P>
<P>
Annan stressed that the Government of Haiti must prepare itself
to assume full responsibility for the further strengthening and
effective functioning of its own institutions, including the
National Police, following the election. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
