<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. to Open Phone Market to Foreigners </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, November 25 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. government plans to
take a major step today to open America's 200 billion-U.S.-dollar
telecommunications market to foreign competition, hoping to lower
international calling rates for consumers and offer chances for
American communications companies elsewhere in the world.
</P>
<P>
The New York Times reported today that the Federal
Communications Commission will vote today to approve rules
carrying out February's World Trade Organization agreement to
liberalize international telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
The ruling will make it much easier for foreign carriers to
offer service in the United States, increasing competition and
potentially driving down prices, it said.
</P>
<P>
The commission also plans to increase to 49 percent from 25
percent the limit on how much of an American communications
carrier can be owned by foreign firms, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
For years, the F.C.C. has forced foreign carriers that want
to offer service between the United States and their home
markets to demonstrate that their native market is open to
American companies. So far only Britain, Sweden and New Zealand
have passed that test, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
Under the new rules, the commission will normally allow
companies from all 132 W.T.O. nations to market to American
customers and deliver services to America's shores, it reported.
</P>
<P>
Major American long-distance companies like AT&AMP;T and the MCI
could see their share of the nation's 12 billion U.S. dollar
international calling market fall as foreign communications giants
like Deutsche Telekom and France Telecom start offering service
directly to American businesses and consumers.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
