<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arab League: Strong Economy Key to Arab Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, November 25 (Xinhua) -- Arab League Secretary General
Esmat Abdel Meguid said today that building a strong Arab economic
base is the best means of protecting Arab world's security and its
civilization identity.
</P>
<P>
In his address read out at the annual conference of Assiut
University Future Studies Center, Assiut, upper Egypt, Meguid
asserted the need for forming an economic grouping to confront
challenges posed by major economic blocs.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the Arabs possess capabilities and potentials
that render them capable of dealing with various blocs from a
position of power.
</P>
<P>
In his address to the conference held under the theme "Arab
Common Market and the Future of Arab Economy", Egyptian Foreign
Minister Amr Moussa said an Arab common market has become a issue
of destiny that would benefit and protect Arab interests in the
light of the current regional and international changes.
</P>
<P>
Moussa referred to present international challenges represented
mainly in the collapse of the Soviet Union and the birth of major
economic blocs and the establishment of the World Trade
Organization and systems on liberalizing world trade.
</P>
<P>
The Arab common market, a concept first formed in the 1960s,
has largely remained on the paper over the years.
</P>
<P>
According to a resolution adopted by the Arab League last year
as a prelude to the Arab common market, the beginning of 1998 will
see the establishment of the Arab Free Trade Area, followed by
gradual elimination of non-tariff and tariff barriers until
complete liberalization was reached by the end of the year 2007.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
