<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's National Fish Presented as Gift to China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 25 (Xinhua) -- The arrival of 108 Nishiki
Carp, Japan's national fish, serves as a reminder of the
hard-earned Sino-Japanese friendship which has stood the test of a
quarter of a century.
</P>
<P>
At a ceremony held in Beijing today, Yosaku Hirasawa, an old
friend of China, presented a special gift to the Chinese people to
mark the 25th anniversary of the normalization of Sino-Japanese
diplomatic ties.
</P>
<P>
The gift includes 100 Nishiki Carp to southwestern China's
Sichuan Province, hometown of the Giant Panda, and eight
25-year-old such fish to Chinese leaders.
</P>
<P>
Just like the Giant Panda, the Nishiki Carp is viewed by the
Japanese people as their national treasure. They have been gifts
to 16 heads of state and government who visited Japan.
</P>
<P>
Because of its colorful and gentle appearance and its long life
of more than 300 years, the Japanese people view the Nishiki Carp
as a symbol of good luck and peace.
</P>
<P>
Yosaku, also a well-known entrepreneur and an expert on
aquaculture, said that peace is most important for people of the
two countries, making the fish an appropriate gift.
</P>
<P>
He said non-governmental friendly exchanges in the 1950s
and 1960s were a major part of the foundation for reforging
bilateral diplomatic ties.
</P>
<P>
Yosaku has visited Sichuan Province several times. He also
donated today 220 million Japanese Yen (1.8 million U.S. dollars)
to help the province set up a center for raising the Nishiki Carp
because of the province's suitable weather and environment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
