<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Starts Building Multi Billion Subway </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, November 25 (Xinhua) -- Singapore started today to
build a long-expected subway line, which will cost some 5 billion
Singapore dollars (about 3.1 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The new subway project, known here as the North-East Line (NEL)
of the Mass Rapid Transit (MRT), is the biggest and most expensive
infrastructure project in Singapore in recent years.
</P>
<P>
Singapore Minister for Communications Mah Bow Tan said at the
ground breaking ceremony today that the start of the construction
of the subway brought the Singaporeans another step closer to a
world class public transport system for Singapore.
</P>
<P>
He said that based on the new financing formula proposed by the
country's Land Transport Authority in its White Paper last year,
the government decided to proceed with the NEL and bring the line
into operation by the year 2002, four years ahead of the original
plan.
</P>
<P>
"In spite of major financial unrest and slower economic growth
in the region, we are able to proceed without interruption with
this project. This is due to the hard work of our people and the
prudence of the Government in accumulating substantial reserves
over the years," the minister said.
</P>
<P>
He said the start of the project is also a reflection of the
government's commitment to investing in the country's basic
infrastructure, in order to enhance the efficiency of Singapore's
transport network.
</P>
<P>
The NEL will run from the World Trade Center, which is located
in the southernmost part of the Singapore island, to Punggol in
the north. There will be 16 stops along the 20-kilometer subway
line.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
