<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Chairs Security Council Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, November 25 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
today chaired a meeting of the Russian Security Council to discuss
scientific personnel training and relation with Chechnya, the
Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, Yeltsin urged the government to complete the
payment of dued wages and subsidies to employees of
budget-financed organizations by January 1, 1998.
</P>
<P>
He noted that Russia is lacking of a system to train personnel
for Russian science and education.
</P>
<P>
Russia's development in the next years and further depends on
how promptly and effectively this issue will be resolved, he said,
adding that "we see the preparation of personnel as part of the
national security."
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin said the state of sciences in the country is directly
linked with the quality of key state decisions, "although this
sphere has not been fine-tuned."
</P>
<P>
He said he is worried about brain drain from Russia. He noted
50 out of the 100 most reputed Russian scientists have left the
country and the exodus of young promising scientists continues.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin said problems of the debts repayment to sciences will
be resolved and wages of school teachers and scientists will be
raised.
</P>
<P>
Today's meeting was attended by Security Council Secretary Ivan
Rybkin, First Deputy Prime Ministers Boris Nemtsov and Anatoly
Chubais and other other officials.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin, Foreign Minister Yevgeny
Primakov and Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev did not participate in
the meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
