<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UAE President Urges Tolerance in Settling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, November 24 (Xinhua) -- United Arab Emirates (UAE)
President Sheikh Zayed Bin Sultan Al-Nahyan today called for
"forgiveness and tolerance" in settling conflicts in the Gulf and
a lifting of sanctions imposed on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Sheikh Zayed, who left here today at the end of his two-day
visit to Egypt, made the remarks during a meeting with chief
editors of Egyptian newspapers.
</P>
<P>
He called for giving Iraqi President Saddam Hussein "another
chance to prove his goodwill," saying that the Iraqi people have
suffered enough from the U.N. sanctions imposed after Iraq's
invasion of Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he described Saddam's reckless thrust into
neighboring Kuwait in 1990 was out of "an ambition coveting the
entire Gulf region."
</P>
<P>
The UAE president criticized attempts to drive a wedge in the
Arab ranks, citing those by Qatari Foreign Minister Sheikh Hamad
Bin Jassim Bin Jabir al-Thani who attacked Egypt.
</P>
<P>
The Qatari foreign minister on November 12 linked Egypt to an
attempted coup against the Gulf Arab state's emir, Sheikh Hamad
Bin Khalifa al-Thani, who toppled his father in a bloodless palace
coup in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Cairo has denied Qatari allegations of its involvement in the
failed coup in Doha last year and has summoned its ambassador to
Qatar for the second time in 18 days for consultations on the
growing strained relations with the small Gulf emirate.
</P>
<P>
Since his arrival here Monday evening, Sheikh Zayed had held
two round of talks with Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak on the
situation in the gulf region, the deadlock in the Mideast peace
process, boosting bilateral ties, and rallying Arab and Islamic
ranks, according to local media reports.
</P>
<P>
This is the second meeting between the two leaders within a
month as Mubarak visited the UAE on October 31 before heading to
Kuala Lumpur to attend the G-15 summit.
</P>
<P>
The UAE is a key trade and economic partner to Egypt. Since it
was established in 1978, the Abu Dhabi Development Fund has pumped
111 million U.S. dollars into various development projects in
Egypt.
</P>
<P>
The UAE is also providing Egypt with financial assistance to
carry out three new irrigation schemes expected to cultivate more
land.
</P>
<P>
In recognition of Sheikh Zayed's contributions to various
agricultural projects nationwide, Egypt has named a giant
irrigation canal under construction in Toshka area after the UAE
leader. 
</P>
</TEXT>
