<HEADLINE> Pakistan Urges India to Fulfill Islamabad Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, November 25 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan today reiterated
that it is ready to hold the fourth round of official talks with
India provided New Delhi honors an agreement reached in June.
</P>
<P>
"It really depends on India, they have reneged on
understanding, they have to come back to Islamabad agreement," a
Foreign Office spokesman told a weekly news conference here today.
</P>
<P>
At the foreign secretary level talks held in Islamabad in late
June, Pakistan and India agreed to set up a mechanism to address
all outstanding issues between them, including the issue of Jammu
and Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
The foreign secretary level talks between the two countries
were resumed in late March this year after being stalled for three
years.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the talks were resumed on the initiative of
Pakistan and that Pakistan was willing to continue the dialogue.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman did not rule out the possibility of a meeting
between Foreign Secretary Shamshad Ahmed and his Indian
counterpart K. Ragunath on the sidelines of the upcoming
ministerial meeting of the South Asian Association for Regional
Cooperation (SAARC) in the Maldives at the end of this month.
</P>
</TEXT>
