<HEADLINE> EU Trade Deficit With Japan Declines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, November 25 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU)'s
trade deficit with Japan has fallen for the fourth consecutive
year to 16.8 billion ECUs last year from 21.4 billion in 1995, it
was learned here today.
</P>
<P>
Imports from Japan fell by 3.3 percent to 52.5 billion ECUs in
1996 and exports rose by 8.4 percent to 35.6 billion ECUs,
according to Eurostat, the EU's statistical office based in
Luxembourg.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, Japan was the EU's third largest trading partner after
the United States and Switzerland, accounting for 7.3 percent of
total value of extra-EU trade.
</P>
<P>
The trade was overwhelmingly in manufactured products, which
represented 98 percent of imports and almost 86 percent of
exports. Machinery and transport equipment accounted for 74
percent of imports and 40 percent of exports.
</P>
<P>
Japan was the source of nearly half of all vehicles imported
into the EU, with a value of 11.7 billion ECUs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
