<HEADLINE> Kurdish Party Accepts Cease-fire in Northern </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, November 25 (Xinhua) -- Iraq's Patriotic Union of
Kurdistan (PUK) has agreed to accept an unconditional cease-fire
with its rival Kurdistan Democratic Party (KDP) in northern Iraq,
a PUK representative said here today.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by the KDP Monday said that the KDP decided
to halt military activities as from 12:00 local time (10:00 GMT)
on November 24.
</P>
<P>
But the cease-fire is conditional upon that the PUK prevents
the outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK) rebels and any other
third party from carrying out military attacks against the KDP
positions or against the civilians across the cease-fire lines in
northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
PUK Representative Shazad Saib in Turkey told Xinhua that "the
PUK has not supported the PKK and there is no any PKK militant in
our region," saying that the PUK agreed to accept the "cease-fire
without any condition."
</P>
<P>
Last Wednesday, Turkish Foreign Ministry spokesman Necati Utkan
accused the PUK of provoking the recent clashes with the KDP in
northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Ankara has repeatedly blamed the PUK for close ties with the
PKK, an outlawed militant group, which has been fighting a
13-year-old war for autonomy in eastern and southeastern Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that the pro-Iranian PUK and the PKK
launched a joint military offensive against the KDP on October 13
and the KDP launched a counter-offensive on November 8, regaining
all lands lost to the PUK and PKK.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Anatolia News Agency today quoted a KDP radio report
as saying that the KDP forces killed 13 PUK militants in the
clashes in Dolaros region of northern Iraq on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The KDP and the PUK, two Kurdish factions, have been fighting
each other for the control of northern Iraq following the 1991
Gulf War, when Iraqi President Saddam Hussein was rendered
ineffectively by allied forces. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
