<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SMEs to Play Vital Role in EU Jobs Creation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, November 25 (Xinhua) -- The small and medium-sized
enterprises (SMEs) in Europe will play an important role in the
creation of jobs in the long run, said a report here today.
</P>
<P>
The fifth annual report of the European Observatory for SMEs
was presented today at a conference organized by the European
Commission, the European Union (EU)'s executive body.
</P>
<P>
The report provides an overview of the current situation
and perspectives of SMEs in all member states of the European
Economic Area and Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
It said that the employment growth, if there is going to be
any, will mainly come from the SMEs.
</P>
<P>
The report "is published at a moment when both the Commission
and the member states are intensifying their efforts for the
implementation of an integrated and coherent strategy in favor of
employment," said Christos Papoutsis, commissioner responsible for
enterprise policy.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of EU member countries approved a total of 19
guidelines for jobs creation across the EU at the jobs summit held
in Luxembourg on November 20-21, which emphasized the importance
of SMEs and enterpreneurship in jobs creation.
</P>
<P>
Papoutsis added that SMEs and the development of a new business
culture could "play a vital role" in tackling the problem of
unemployment.
</P>
<P>
He expressed his determination to strengthen the policies which
would help the EU create the new business mentality and a new
business environment so that the SMEs will become more competitive
and create the new jobs needed by Europe.
</P>
<P>
About one million new enterprises are started in the EU each
year. On average, a European enterprise provides employment for
six persons, said the report, which was prepared by the European
Network for SME Research.
</P>
<P>
However, the report said that employment created by new
enterprise is rather unstable, as failure rates of new businesses
are quite high. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
