<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korea, Japan Continue Fishery Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, November 25 (Xinhua) -- South Korea and Japan will open
three days of fishery talks here on Wednesday to settle
differences over revising the 1965 bilateral fishing accord.
</P>
<P>
South Korean Foreign Minister Yoo Chong-ha and his Japanese
counterpart, Keizo Obuchi, agreed to hold the talks when they met
last week in Vancouver, Canada, a foreign ministry spokesman said
today.
</P>
<P>
A two-day meeting on Japan's unilaterally declared straight
base line also opened here today, with delegations led by the
deputy director generals of the two foreign ministries present.
</P>
<P>
The fishery talks, the seventh this year, will focus on how to
map out a temporary revision to the current fishery agreement and
how to guarantee the vested fishing rights of one country in the
other's waters, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Such a provisional approach is aimed at preventing overlapping
claims to sovereignty over rocky islets in the middle of the sea
between them.
</P>
<P>
The talks come after Seoul expressed eagerness for an early
conclusion of a revised fishing accord.
</P>
<P>
Yoo Chong-ha said in Seoul last week that South Korea is ready
to conclude a new fishing agreement with Japan as early as the end
of the year.
</P>
<P>
However, Yoo said Seoul would accept a new fishing accord with
Japan providing it does not harm its sovereignty over the Tokdo
islets (Takeshima in Japanese), and the existing rights of the
South Korean fishermen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971125.0086 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 20 African States Face Food Shortage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, November 25 (Xinhua) -- Twenty African countries
continue to face exceptional food emergencies due to adverse
weather conditions and, in some cases, civil strife, according to
a U.N. report reaching here today.
</P>
<P>
Food shortage is particularly acute in Sierra Leone, eastern
Africa and the Great Lakes region, said the latest report on the
continent's food supply situation and crop prospects issued by
the U.N. Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO).
</P>
<P>
It says a severe drought at the beginning of this year
substantially reduced second-season food production in Kenya,
Tanzania, Uganda, Somalia and large parts of southern Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, late or erratic rainfall later this year have led
to reduced main-season harvest in Tanzania, Uganda and Kenya
where the cereal production will fall by 30, 27 and 22 percent
respectively compared to 1996, the report estimated.
</P>
<P>
The Tanzanian government estimates that about three million
people are facing severe food shortages and has recently appealed
for 76,000 tons of emergency food aid.
</P>
<P>
In Ethiopia, despite an overall satisfactory food supply
situation, it is officially estimated that some 4.6 million
people are in need of food aid.
</P>
<P>
Food supply is tight throughout Somalia where farmers' stocks
are exhausted after three consecutive poor harvests.
</P>
<P>
In the Great Lakes region, despite the easing of refugee
crisis, serious food difficulties persist, largely as a result of
major population dislocations, continuing insecurity and
unfavorable weather in some areas, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The food situation in Sierra Leone has continued to
deteriorate since the coup in May. Food prices have increased
sharply and serious food shortages are reported.
</P>
<P>
There are currently more than 92,000 internally displaced
people in Sierra Leone, up from about 65,000 before the coup.
</P>
<P>
The level of the cereal import requirement in sub-Saharan
Africa in 1997/98 is likely to be higher than in the previous
year, the report concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
