<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Medicine Benefits People All over the World </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 25 (Xinhua) -- Traditional Chinese medical
science has gained adherents throughout the world and demonstrated
its value, public health officials said here at today's meeting of
Chinese medical circles.
</P>
<P>
Since 1987, China has trained 14,700 foreign students from more
than 130 countries and regions in traditional Chinese medicine.
</P>
<P>
The World Health Organization (WHO) has established seven
traditional cooperative study centers and three acupuncture
training centers in China.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the country annually exports Chinese medicine
valued at 600 million U.S. dollars to 130 countries and regions.
</P>
<P>
WHO and many foreign countries have invited practitioners of
traditional Chinese medicine as visiting professors.
</P>
<P>
The popularity of traditional Chinese medicine will benefit the
health of people all over the world, said Zhang Wenkang, Vice
Minister of Health.
</P>
<P>
"We should cultivate more personnel for international medical
exchange," said Zhang, also director of the State Administration
of Traditional Chinese Medicine.
</P>
<P>
During the last 30 years, hundreds of medical groups consisting
of traditional Chinese medical workers have been sent from China
to other countries, especially developing nations, according to
officials who attended the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Participants in the medical conference were also scheduled to
study a 10-year development project for medicine. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
