<DOCNO> XIE19971125.0092 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-25 14:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Khartoum Calls for Improvement of Ties With Cairo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM, November 25 (Xinhua) -- Sudanese Foreign Minister Ali
Othman Taha has said that relations between Sudan and Egypt should
be improved as tension will prejudice the strategic interests of
the two countries.
</P>
<P>
He was quoted by Ra'e El-Aakher newspaper today as saying
before the Sudanese parliament Monday that Sudan was serious in
its efforts to resume the brotherly ties with Egypt.
</P>
<P>
The Sudanese minister added that he would make public the
measures taken by his country in this direction soon.
</P>
<P>
Relations between Cairo and Khartoum went chilled after Egypt
accused Sudan of involving in a 1995 assassination attempt on
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak in Addis Ababa, Ethiopia. Sudan
denied such a charge.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Taha stressed that reviving relations with Saudi
Arabia and resuming relations with Kuwait were among the top
priorities of the Sudanese government towards the Arab and Islamic
states.
</P>
<P>
He expressed appreciation of the Kuwaiti government for
forgiving the wrong doings of some Arab brothers including Sudan,
apparently referring to the positions of some Arab nations which
sided with Iraq during the Gulf war.
</P>
<P>
The Sudanese minister briefed the parliament on the moves taken
by his government that led to the strengthening of the ties with
Syria, Jordan, Iraq, Yemen, Morocco, and Libya. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971125.0093 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Some OPEC Members Predict Oil Production Increase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, November 25 (Xinhua) -- Some members of the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) have
predicted that there will be an increase in the OPEC's production
ceiling.
</P>
<P>
The ceiling will rise from the current 25.033 million barrels
per day (bpd) to 27 million bpd, Iranian Oil Minister Bijan Namdar
Zangeneh said upon his arrival at Soekarno-Hatta International
Airport here today.
</P>
<P>
He said the production quota issue will be taken up during the
103rd ministerial meeting of the OPEC to be held here from
November 26 to December 1 with the participation of 11 member
countries.
</P>
<P>
He also predicted that the world's oil demand will grow by
about 2 million bpd next year from the current 73.7 million bpd to
75 million bpd.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Saudi Petroleum Minister Ali al-Naimi said upon his
arrival here that oil prices "can be better."
</P>
<P>
But, he refused to comment on whether the OPEC should raise its
production quota.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia, the world's largest oil producer, accounts for 32
percent of OPEC output. It said several weeks ago that it favored
an increase of 2 million barrels a day to around 27 million
barrels.
</P>
<P>
But that was before talks of a possible rise in Iraqi output
under its oil-for-food arrangement with the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait's Oil Minister Isa al-Mazeedi on Monday renewed his
country's call for a higher individual OPEC quota if the group
agrees to raise its current overall production ceiling of 25.03
million bpd.
</P>
<P>
Analysts say that despite expected higher world oil demand next
year, an increase in the OPEC quota plus a rise in Iraqi output
would be too much for the market and could push prices down.
</P>
<P>
However, Libyan Energy Minister Abdullah Salem el-Baderi said
here today that his country wants the OPEC to maintain its
production quota at the current level.
</P>
<P>
OPEC oil ministers will officially begin their semi-annual
meeting here Wednesday to decide whether to raise the quota for
the first time since September 1993 and how to accommodate resumed
Iraqi oil production.
</P>
<P>
The OPEC groups Algeria, Ecuador, Gabon, Indonesia, Iran,
Kuwait, Libya, Nigeria, Qatar, Saudi Arabia, the United Arab
Emirates, Venezuela and Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
