<HEADLINE> EU Increases Funding for Ukraine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, November (Xinhua) -- The European Union will increase
financial assistance to Ukraine under its TACIS program in 1998,
although funds for other East European countries will be reduced,
a newspaper report here said today.
</P>
<P>
Ukraine will receive 44 million ECUs (about 50 million
U.S. dollars), up from the 40 million ECUs (about 45 million
dollars) in 1997.
</P>
<P>
"The increase signifies the importance of Ukraine to the
European Union," said Hugues Mingartelli, head of the European
Commission's unit for Ukraine, Moldova and Belarus.
</P>
<P>
He said the money would be used to launch about 20 new projects
in Ukraine, most of them aimed at institutional reforming and
promoting development in private commercial and energy sectors.
</P>
<P>
However, Mingartelli did not give a complete list of projects,
saying the package has yet to be approved by several EU member
countries.
</P>
<P>
"The priorities for programs are decided here, in Ukraine, and
not in Brussels," said Alexander Brodsky, deputy head of a
Ukrainian economic agency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
