<HEADLINE> China to Send Charity Personnel to Study in Hong Kong (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 25 (Xinhua) -- China's largest charity will
send its personnel to train in Hong Kong to learn standard
international practices of managing the non-profit organizations,
its senior official said today.
</P>
<P>
China Charity Federation (CCF) plans to organize 50 leaders of
local Chinese non-profit agencies to take part in the Hong Kong
training course for charity business professionals in February.
The training course is financially sponsored by United Way
International (UWI), a U.S.-based voluntary organization.
</P>
<P>
The training course is one of many international cooperative
endeavors of the federation, China's only national charity with
links to 34 other groups worldwide.
</P>
<P>
UWI also has invited CCF leaders to attend UWI's annual
meeting, which is scheduled for May of 1998 in Miami, Florida.
</P>
<P>
Robert Beggan, UWI president, praised the hard work and
achievements of his Chinese colleagues during a recent Beijing
tour.
</P>
<P>
"We expect further cooperation with China Charity Federation,"
said Beggan. "We'd like to help the largest humanitarian
organization in China."
</P>
<P>
After visiting a senior citizens home and a retarded children's
center, Beggan said that he was impressed by the neat environment
and efficient management.
</P>
