<DOCNO> XIE19971125.0106 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Seoul Bourse Unrest Over Worries About IMF Package </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, November 25 (Xinhua) -- Amid growing fears of chain
business collapses and a belt-tightening economy in the aftermath
of a bailout by the International Monetary Fund (IMF), South
Korean stock prices tumbled today to a 10-year low for the second
consecutive day.
</P>
<P>
The leading composite index at the Seoul bourse plunged 11.05
points to 439.59, the lowest level since July 9, 1987, when the
index stood at 441.02.
</P>
<P>
During the day, the index once declined to 423.71 points, but
resurged on the back of the government's announcement that it
would review the possibility of introducing long-term bonds which
will not necessitate a background check on the source of the funds.
</P>
<P>
Market analysts said panic about an inevitable restructuring in
the business sector prompted bond yields to rise sharply. The
yield for three-year maturity bonds shot up 1.55 percentage points
to 17.6 percent, the highest level in five-and-a-half years.
</P>
<P>
Even though interest rates have greatly increased, the bonds,
including those issued by affiliates belonging to the top three
business groups, did not attract any buyers.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the South Korean won remained weak against the U.S.
dollar, mainly because of strong demand for the greenback among
foreign currency-thirsty merchant banks, dealers said.
</P>
<P>
The won, which lost the strength it regained over the few days
until Monday, closed at a further-sagging 1,122 against the
dollar, putting the base rate to be posted at 1,117.50 won on
Wednesday, up 17 won over Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Market experts predicted that the stock market would undergo a
further decline to the level of 400 points and the won would
remain at the 1,100 level for the time being.
</P>
<P>
A growing number of bankruptcies in troubled companies and
financial institutions would occur since the IMF is expected to
demand more painful steps to stablize the financial markets as
well as restructuring the debts-laden industries, they said.
</P>
<P>
South Korean and the IMF officials started their two or three
weeks' negotiations on the conditions for the IMF rescue loan on
Monday. The first batch of bailouts will come in mid-December.
</P>
<P>
In response to foreign press reports that the 20-billion-dollar
loan applied by Seoul will not be sufficient to resolve the
current financial crisis, a senior government official said Monday
that his government is considering a package of 50 billion
U.S. dollars. 
</P>
