<HEADLINE> Vice Premier Discusses Role of Education in Economic Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, November 25 (Xinhua) -- Vice Premier Li Lanqing
stressed the importance of education and opening up China's
central and western areas to economic development.
</P>
<P>
Li, also a Standing Committee member of the Political Bureau of
the Communist Party of China's (CPC) Central Committee, made these
remarks during a four-day tour this month in central China's Hubei
Province.
</P>
<P>
In his visit to institutions of higher education, primary and
middle schools in Wuhan, capital of Hubei from 21 to 24 of this
month, Li told teachers that China's modernization largely depends
on quality of citizens and skilled personnel, and that the country's
educational reforms should be deepened.
</P>
<P>
He urged all schools of fundamental education to abandon the
traditional mode of exam-oriented education and turn to quality
education to help students grow up comprehensively and healthily.
</P>
<P>
"The educational quality of a school should be judged by what
kind of people it fosters for the society, instead of merely by
its students' performance in the entrance examinations for
instutions of higher learning," he said.
</P>
<P>
He also urged local governments to ensure the quality of
textbooks and to take effective measures to improve both the
general quality and living conditions of the teachers, especially
those in primary and secondary schools.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting with participants of a symposium on investment
and development of central Chinese areas, Li pointed out that the
15th CPC National Congress reiterated that opening up to the
outside world is one of China's long-term basic policies.
</P>
<P>
"With rich resources, a vast market and growing state support,
the central and western regions are gaining more advantages in
development and opening up," he added.
</P>
<P>
He urged the central and western areas to make greater
efforts at reforms and combine the opening-up drive with a
strategic reshuffle of the state-owned economy.  
</P>
</TEXT>
