<HEADLINE> Orchestra Touring China to Play German, Austrian Music </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 24 (Xinhua) -- Rhine River musicians will
offer Chinese audiences the best of German and Austrian music
during their Chinese tour Nov. 26-30.
</P>
<P>
According to the China Performing Arts Agency (CPAA), the
Saarbrucken Radio Symphony Orchestra will give several concerts in
Tianjin, Shanghai and Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Chief conductor Michael Stern has directed such well-known
symphonies as the Orchestra National de Lyon in France and the
Tonhalle Orchestra Zurich.
</P>
<P>
"Stern is a firm believer in the responsibility of performers
to present the music of their time, and he is also active in
introducing new and little-known works," said a spokesman for
sponsoring CPAA.
</P>
<P>
The CPAA calls the upcoming performance a good combination of
East and West, because its soloist are two Chinese musicians
living abroad -- Wang Jian on cello and Han Xiaoming on horn.
</P>
<P>
Wang Jian studied cello with his father when he was four years
old. "During his years at the Shanghai Conservatory of Music he
was heard by renowned cellist Aldo Parisot, who was so impressed
that he arranged for the young artist to enter the Yale School of
Music in 1985," the spokesman said. At the age of 11, he won
international acclaim.
</P>
<P>
The upcoming five-day series of concerts will give Chinese
music lovers an opportunity to appreciate the works of such
classical composers as Richard Wagner, Joseph Haydn and Johannes
Brahms. 
