<HEADLINE> Indonesia-China Trade May Hit 4 Billion U.S. Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, November 25 (Xinhua) -- Trade between Indonesia and
China continues to increase and is expected to reach about 4
billion U.S. dollars by the end of this year, a noted businessman
said.
</P>
<P>
The Singapore-based Indonesian shipping magnate, Tong Djoe,
said here today that trade and investment between the two nations
will greatly increase if Indonesia could strengthen its
cooperation with China's small and medium-sized enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Trade and investment cooperation between the two countries has
been carried out by big businesses while China's potentials are in
its small and medium-sized businesses, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Trade value between Indonesia and China in 1995 was recorded at
3.49 billion dollars and it increased to 3.71 billion dollars in
1996.
</P>
<P>
"Both countries' trading value this year is expected to
increase as in the first semester of 1997 alone the figure already
reached almost 3 billion U.S. dollars," said Tong Djoe, who plays
an important role in promoting trade between Indonesia and China.
</P>
<P>
Indonesian commodities in demand in China are plywood, pulp,
crude palm oil, natural rubber and coffee.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia, meanwhile, imports from China generators, cotton and
other goods.  
</P>
</TEXT>
