<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Commission Calls for Rights for EU Citizens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, November 25 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission today
kicked off the second phase of the Citizens First initiative, a
campaign to create awareness among the EU citizens about their
rights.
</P>
<P>
Under the initiative, the EU's executive body called for
citizen rights concerning equal opportunities between men and
women, consumer protection, buying goods and services in other
member states and traveling within the EU.
</P>
<P>
"Citizens First is a practical and effective means of raising
people's awareness about their rights in the EU," said Mario
Monti, EU commissioner responsible for single market affairs.
</P>
<P>
He added that the program was aimed at informing EU citizens of
their rights and how they can use them in practice in order to
make a success of the planned single market.
</P>
<P>
The second phase, which builds on the formula of the first
phase of Citizens First, is aimed to provide EU citizens with
clear and factual information on the rights and opportunities
people have as a result of the EU and on what to do if these
rights are denied.
</P>
<P>
Since the launching of the first phase in November 1996, some
75 million people across the EU have become aware of the program,
according to the Commission.
</P>
<P>
It says that more than one million people have contacted
Citizens First via the free phone numbers and the Internet site to
obtain guides and fact sheets concerning their rights to work,
live and study in another EU country.
</P>
<P>
However, EU surveys have revealed that though people are
interested in the areas covered by the second phase of the
initiative, they are still not always aware of their basic rights.
</P>
<P>
Some young people expect that it will become easier to travel
around the EU in ten years' time and yet do not realize how easy
it is already, says the survey, adding that almost half of young
people in the EU have not made a visit to another member state in
the last two years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
