<HEADLINE> Remains of American Air Crew Turned Over to U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUILIN, November 25 (Xinhua) -- Part of the remains of an
American military air crew who died in a crash in Guangxi during
World War II were turned over today to a field survey team from
the United States.
</P>
<P>
This is the second time the Chinese side has turned over
remains of the air crew to the United States. The first was on
January 15, this year.
</P>
<P>
More than half a century ago, during World War II, a U.S. Army
Air Corps B-24 bomber crashed in the Maoershan Mountains in
Xingan County in southern China's Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has assisted a team of experts in the
second search for crew members' remains.
</P>
<P>
A plank road along the face of a cliff was jointly built by the
Chinese and Americans to carry out the search work. Because of the
size of the area to be searched and bad weather, the U.S. team was
unable to thoroughly complete the search work. They plan to return
next year for a third search.
</P>
<P>
At today's transfer ceremony, the leader of the U.S. team -- on
behalf of his government, relatives of the dead crew, and the
whole American people -- offered hanks to the Chinese government
at all levels and Guangxi residents for their humanitarian
support. 
</P>
</TEXT>
