<HEADLINE> Chinese Scientists Plan to Clone Rare Monkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 25 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scientists plan to
carry out a cloning project in the near future to increase the
number of Yunnan snub-nosed monkeys, according to today's
"People's Daily."
</P>
<P>
Scientists with the Kunming Zoological Research Institute are
using advanced technology to research hereditary features of the
primate in preparation for the cloning, the report said, but gave
no details.
</P>
<P>
"This is the third kind of protective ways for the rare
species, other than creating nature reserves and keeping them in
captivity," the report said, adding that the protection of this
rare primate could have a bright future.
</P>
<P>
Yunnan snub-nosed monkeys, also known as golden monkeys, are on
the brink of extinction.
</P>
<P>
Researchers at the institute, under the Chinese Academy of
Sciences, have bred 13 such monkeys in captivity since 1994 with
the aid of reproductive research, the report said.
</P>
<P>
They have conducted an overall investigation of the monkeys'
living conditions in the wild since they were discovered in
southwestern China's Yunnan Province a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
Nature reserves of the Yunnan snub-nosed monkeys have been
established in the northwestern part of the province.
</P>
<P>
"However, we are still facing problems, such as damage to the
monkey's habitats caused by excessive lumbering and a shortage of
research funds," said Ji Weizhi, director of the institute.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
