<HEADLINE> French Communist Leader Excludes Merger with Socialists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, November 25 (Xinhua) -- The National Secretary of the
French Communist Party (PCF), Robert Hue, today excluded the
possibility of a merger between his party and the Socialist Party,
because, he said, it would weaken the leftist force in France.
</P>
<P>
"The reversal of the Congress of Tours is out of the question,"
said Hue in a television interview. He was referring to the 1920
Congress of Tours held by the French Socialists, which resulted in
the creation of the PCF.
</P>
<P>
But he expressed his support to "all which can contribute to
improving the conditions of the union" with the Socialists through
a "unitary pact for progress."
</P>
<P>
He said the PCF and the Socialist Party could present common
candidates in the regional elections scheduled for March 1998.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Henri Weber, a French senator from the Socialist
Party, said that "ideologically, it is from now possible" to
reverse the Congress of Tours. He was writing in the PCF daily,
L'Humanite. 
</P>
