<HEADLINE> Kenyan Police Ordered to Probe Election Campaign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, November 25 (Xinhua) -- The Kenya Electoral
Commission (EC) has directed the police commissioner to launch
immediate investigation into the reported incidents of election
campaign violence in the country.
</P>
<P>
The Daily Nation today quoted the EC Chairman Zacchaeus
Chesoni as saying on Monday that the commission had moved to stem
violence during the campaign period when some presidential
opposition candidates were reported to have been subjected to
pre-poll violence.
</P>
<P>
The motorcade of the Democratic Party Presidential candidate
Mwai Kibaki was reportedly stoned in Kiambu town, about 20
kilometers north of Nairobi, minutes after he addressed a
campaign rally in the town on November 15.
</P>
<P>
Raila Odinga, who is vying on an opposition National
Development Party ticket, escaped with minor injuries when youths
stoned his motorcade last Saturday in Kisii District, southwest
Kenya.
</P>
<P>
The EC Chairman noted that the electoral code agreed on during
the Inter-Party Parliamentary Group talks empowers the commission
to bar a candidate or party from campaigning if found guilty of
encouraging violence.
</P>
<P>
He warned that it was an infringement of the code to publish
and repeat false, defamatory or inflammatory allegations
concerning any candidate or party.
</P>
<P>
The local newspaper East African Standard today reported that
at least two people were killed and scores injured as election
campaign violence escalated in various parts of Kenya.
</P>
<P>
A campaign manager to Lugari parliamentary aspirant Cyrus
Jirongo of the ruling Kenya African National Union was shot dead
by thugs during a door-to-door campaign.
</P>
<P>
The second victim was a youth who was stabbed to death as
rowdy mobs clashed over campaign cash handouts in Machakos
District, about 80 kilometers south of Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
Chesoni appealed to candidates to assist the commission to
enforce the electoral code by restraining supporters from acts of
violence, threats of violence or incitement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
