<HEADLINE> UN Arms Inspectors Continue Mission in Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, November 25 (Xinhua) -- Six inspection teams of the
United Nations Special Commission (UNSCOM) overseeing the
dismantling of Iraq's weapons of mass destruction continue their
mission today, the Iraqi News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The teams set out between 8:30 and 9:30 local time (0530 and
0630 GMT) to inspect a number of suspected sites for making
weapons, according to the agency.
</P>
<P>
This was the fourth consecutive day that U.N. arms experts
undertake their work after Iraq allowed them back on Friday ending
a three-week standoff.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has been cooperating with the UNSCOM, hoping that it will
finish its inspection mission as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
The commission will certify if Iraq has complied with the
orders issued in 1991 to destroy all its nuclear, chemical and
biological weapons.
</P>
<P>
Only then will the U.N. Security Council lift the economic
sanctions, including a ban on oil export, imposed on Iraq
following its invasion of Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
But U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen Sunday accused Iraq of
barring U.N. inspectors from entering 63 sites, warning of the
possibility of rekindling a crisis.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Baghdad asserted that Iraq and UNSCOM have reached
an agreement that arms inspectors should not do anything that may
jeopardize Iraq's sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, the inspectors should not enter the
"sensitive" sites like presidential palaces that represent Iraq's
sovereignty, it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
