<HEADLINE> Kenya's Economic Growth Rate to Fall: Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, November 25 (Xinhua) -- The growth rate of Kenya's
economy is expected to be 3.6 percent this year, down from the
4.2 percent in last year, a central bank official said.
</P>
<P>
The Daily Nation newspaper today quoted Thomas Kibua, deputy
governor of the Central Bank of Kenya, as saying that the
expected drop in tourism earnings, lack of investor confidence
and the uncertainty associated with elections would lead to a
growth rate of about 3.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
He told an annual dinner of the Kenya Institute of Bankers
that the performance of the economy and the banking industry was
expected to improve next year due to improved earnings from
tourism and less investors' anxiety after the elections.
</P>
<P>
The bank official pointed out that the major challenges for
Kenya's economy would be maintaining low inflation and a stable
Shilling exchange rate.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the World Economic Outlook for October published by
the International Monetary Fund (IMF) predicted that Kenya's
economy would increase by 3.5 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
The IMF publication attributed the lower growth rate to the
drought and El Nino rains suffered in most parts of the country,
the violence linked to the demands for constitutional reforms and
skirmishes at the coastal region adversely affecting the
country's tourism.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan Vice-President George Saitoti projected a 5.2 percent
growth rate for Kenya's economy this year in the 1997 Economic
Survey issued last June. 
</P>
</TEXT>
