<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Seeks $406 Million of Humanitarian Aid for Balkan States </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, November 25 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations is calling
for 406 million U.S. dollars in 1998 for its humanitarian programs
in Bosnia, Croatia, Yugoslavia and Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
In the two years after the signing of the Dayton accord,
noticeable progress has been achieved by the international
community to help the region overcome the war destruction build
lasting peace, said the UN Department of Humanitarian Affairs in a
press release Monday.
</P>
<P>
However, it pointed out, much still remains to be done. Up to
1.6 million displaced persons and refugees remain uprooted;
several million landmines continue to threaten lives and impede
rehabilitation and return of people; and much of the
infrastructure in the war-impacted areas, ranging from individual
homes through key services, are yet to be rehabilitated.
</P>
<P>
The programs contained in the Consolidated Inter-Agency Appeal
for 1998 will have a major role to play in meeting such needs.
</P>
<P>
The appeal covers the proposed activities of various UN
agencies including the UN High Commissioner for Refugees, the UN
Development Program, World Food Program, the UN Children's Fund
and the World Health Organization. 
</P>
</TEXT>
