<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon's National Carrier Under Investigation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, November 25 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon's national carrier, the
Middle East Airlines (MEA), is under investigation over a leasing
deal of three planes with Singapore Airlines, the Beirut Times
newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon's judicial department has requested the MEA to submit
its monthly financial report for the investigation, according to
the paper.
</P>
<P>
The MEA reportedly paid a large commission to Marwan Fouad
Bardawil, son of Lebanese prominent businessman Fouad Bardawil, to
negotiate the deal with Singapore Airlines.
</P>
<P>
This has violated the ban of the national carrier on using
intermediaries in such deals or paying commissions.
</P>
<P>
Marwan Fouad Bardawil has been arrested for allegedly accepting
the money, according to the paper.
</P>
<P>
But Khaled Salam, chairman of the MEA said the airlines is not
involved in any unethical deal.
</P>
<P>
"We usually negotiate the leasing of planes with any foreign
firm directly, without the need to go through a third party to
finalize the deal," he said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the leasing deal of the three planes has been
approved by MEA's board of directors several months ago.
</P>
<P>
The MEA will pay 39 million U.S. dollars to Singapore Airlines
to lease the three planes for five years, according to Salam.
</P>
<P>
He revealed that the MEA has filed a law suit months ago
against Bardawil and Singapore Airlines, which he accused of
breaching their contract by paying commissions to the arrestee to
help win the deal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
