<DOCNO> XIE19971125.0133 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK People More Confident About Anti-Corruption </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, November 25 (Xinhua) -- An annual survey conducted
by the Independent Commission Against Corruption (ICAC) today
revealed a significant increase in public confidence in the body.
</P>
<P>
According to the survey, 85.7 percent of respondents said their
confidence in the ICAC will increase or remain the same in the
coming year.
</P>
<P>
"This year's survey results showed that the public have become
more optimistic about the control of corruption and that public
confidence in the ICAC has increased significantly," said Prof.
Wong Siu-lun, Convenor of the Community Research Sub-Committee of
the ICAC's Citizens Advisory Committee on Community Relations.
</P>
<P>
The smooth transition and the ICAC's effective work in the past
year boosted the confidence, he said.
</P>
<P>
A total of 76.5 percent of respondents considered the ICAC's
anti-corruption work effective or very effective, which
represented an increase of 7.4 percentage points when compared
with last year.
</P>
<P>
Seventy percent of those surveyed considered the ICAC impartial
in its investigation work, which represented an improvement of
10.5 percentage points over last year.
</P>
<P>
As regards the finding that 55.2 percent of those polled said
the ICAC had not done enough to make its own work known to the
public, ICAC's Director of Community Relations Miss Janet Wong
Wing-chen said the ICAC will continue to enhance its transparency
through the media and direct contact.
</P>
<P>
A 13 episode-spot series on the ICAC's work will be telecast on
a local channel starting from tomorrow, followed by the English
version in March next year. A new drama series to be produced by
the ICAC itself will be released in the coming summer, she said.
</P>
<P>
She said the ICAC will step up preventive education in the
business sector and strengthen moral education for students as
well as young people at work.
</P>
<P>
In the first 10 months of this year, 2,471 reports alleging
corruption were received by the ICAC, down 4 percent from the same
period of last year.
</P>
<P>
The ICAC has conducted annual surveys to gauge the public's
views on issues such as the corruption scene in Hong Kong and
ICAC's performance. This year's survey was carried out by MDR
Technology Ltd. between July 14 and 18, with a total of 1,104
respondents interviewed through telephone. 
</P>
</TEXT>
