<HEADLINE> Russian Military Representative Starts Work in NATO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, November 25 (Xinhua) -- A senior Russian military
representative to NATO today paid his initial office call at the
Western military alliance.
</P>
<P>
Lieutenant General Viktor Savarzin was received by NATO
Military Committee Chairman Klaus Naumann, who is NATO's military
authority.
</P>
<P>
During their meeting, Naumann and Savarzin discussed the
preparation for the forthcoming meeting of the military committee
with the Russian chief of general staff.
</P>
<P>
Savarzin served as commander of joint peace-keeping forces in
Tajikistan before being appointed by the military commission of
the Russian Federation as the country's representative to NATO.
</P>
<P>
The lieutenant general will attend the inaugural meeting of
military representatives under the auspices of the NATO-Russia
Permanent Joint Council (PJC) on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The PJC held its fourth meeting at ambassadorial level Monday
to exchange views on peace-keeping operations in Bosnia in the
wake of the National Assembly elections in the Republika Srpska.
</P>
<P>
The meeting also discussed NATO-Russia cooperation in the
NATO-led Stabilization Force in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
NATO and Russia also exchanged views on the PJC work program
for 1998 which will be approved by NATO ministers in December.
The ambassadors underscored the need to increase defense-related
and military cooperation between NATO and Russia.
</P>
<P>
This year's work program was approved at the first PJC
ministerial meeting held on September 26 in New York. 
</P>
</TEXT>
