<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Murder Cases Decrease in KwaZulu Natal Province, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, November 25 (Xinhua) -- The murder rate in South
Africa's KwaZulu Natal Province is down by 10.5 percent from
January to September this year compared to the same period in
1996, Premier Ben Ngubane said.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a two-day provincial crime prevention summit in
Durban Monday, Ngubane said attempted murder had decreased by 9.8
percent and armed robbery had also shown a significant drop.
</P>
<P>
However, rape had increased by 2.4 percent and stock theft by
6.4 percent, he said.
</P>
<P>
The premier commended provincial police for their active role
in combating crime in the province. He also attributed much of
their success to the public and their commitment and loyalty in
assisting police in investigations.
</P>
<P>
Ngubane stressed the fight against crime could not be left to
law enforcement agencies, saying, "the communities must be an
equally active partner."
</P>
<P>
KwaZulu Natal Province is believed to be one of provinces
where crimes and violence activities are high on alert.
</P>
<P>
The summit was part of a national crime preventiont strategy
organized by the Safety and Security Ministry to implement crime
prevention programs.
</P>
<P>
The meeting would discuss, among others, urban crime
prevention, youth as victims and perpetrators of crime, violence
against women and violence in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
Similar summits had already been held in other eight
provinces. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
