<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Political Stalemate Continues in India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, November 25 (Xinhua) -- The political stalemate
arising from a report on the assassination of former Prime
Minister Rajiv Gandhi continued today as the Congress party is yet
to respond to a letter of reconciliation from Prime Minister Inder
Kumar Gujral.
</P>
<P>
The interim report, based on investigation into the 1991
assassination, accused the Dravida Munnetra Kazagham (DMK), a
major constituent of the ruling United Front, of involvement in
the incident.
</P>
<P>
Since the report was tabled in the parliament on November 20,
the Congress party has been demanding the ouster of the three DMK
ministers from the Gujral government, warning that it would
withdraw support for the government if its demand is not met.
</P>
<P>
The United Front government depends on the support of the
Congress party for sustaining a majority in the lower house of the
parliament.
</P>
<P>
In a letter delivered to Congress party President Sitaram Kesri
on Monday night, Gujral rejected the demand but offered to talk
with the party to seek a way out of the current political crisis.
</P>
<P>
The Congress Working Committee, the supreme decision-making
body of the Congress party, met here briefly on Monday night after
the letter was delivered to Kesri but deferred a response to the
letter.
</P>
<P>
The committee is likely to meet again later today to consider
Gujral's letter, the Press Trust of India reported.
</P>
<P>
United Front sources said a meeting of the core committee of
the 13-party front is likely to be held in the evening after the
Congress party responds to the prime minister's letter.  
</P>
</TEXT>
