<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cholera Claims 35 in S. Nigeria State </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, November 25 (Xinhua) -- Cholera has killed 35 persons
in southern Nigeria's Edo State since the outbreak of the disease
was reported in August this year.
</P>
<P>
Due to poor water supply, more than 80 percent of residents in
the Owan East Local Government Area are suffering from
water-borne diseases following the outbreak of cholera,
guinea-worm diseases and river blindness, the Guardian newspaper
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to an on-going World Bank dam project, 20 communities
will soon enjoy safe water supply, Council Chairman Chief Monday
Iriabije said, while appealing to local residents to be calm.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Petroleum Trust Fund, a government-backed
organization specialized in investing in infrastructure
construction with money drawn from sales of fuel, would
rehabilitate seven bore-holes, five abandoned water works and
sink 11 open wells to boost water supply in the area. 
</P>
</TEXT>
