<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa's Trade Surplus Grows Sharply in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, November 25 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's trade
surplus rose sharply to 1.73 billion Rand (360 million U.S.
Dollars) in October from 144 million Rand (nearly 30 million
Dollars) in September, reflecting a 30 percent surge in exports.
</P>
<P>
The trade surplus far exceeded the consensus forecast of 620
million Rand (130 million Dollars), the Business Day newspaper
said today.
</P>
<P>
The trade surplus from January to October is 11.45 billion
Rand (2.4 billion Dollars), an increase of 37 percent from a year
earlier.
</P>
<P>
Customs and excise figures released Monday showed that exports
were 14.73 billion Rand in October, up from 11.35 billion in
September.
</P>
<P>
Manufactured exports have performed particularly well, making
up for gold's lackluster performance. Machinery and transport
equipment exports remained the star performers, with growth of
about 45 percent in the first 10 months of the year.
</P>
<P>
Although imports rose to almost 13 billion Rand in October
from 11.21 billion in September, economists said the growth was
less worrying as the bill had been boosted by oil purchases.
</P>
<P>
When oil was excluded, imports in October were up only 7
percent month on month and 5.5 percent year on year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
