<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asia to Build Sustainable Cities into 21st Century </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, November 25 (Xinhua) -- Hundreds of delegates from
the Asia-Pacific region gathered here today at an environment
conference to discuss how the fast-growing Asian cities can
maintain sustained development into the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
The Pollution in the Metropolitan and Urban Environment
(POLMET) conference, held every three years since 1985, centered
its theme this year on "Sustainability in the 21st century -- The
Challenge for Asian Cities."
</P>
<P>
Asia has achieved rapid economic growth over the past decade,
but at the same time the region has to face increasingly severe
environmental problems for lack of properly integrated policies,
financial resources and technical know-how, according to the
organizer, the Hong Kong Institution of Engineers.
</P>
<P>
The three-day meeting provides a forum for policy makers,
professionals and business executives from some 30 countries and
regions to address inter-relationships between society, economy
and environment.
</P>
<P>
Xie Zhenhua, head of China's National Environmental Protection
Agency, kicked off the keynote session today by delivering a
speech titled "Building sustainable cities". He said: "It is
possible to strike a balance between fast economic growth and a
clean living environment so as to attain the goal of
sustainability."
</P>
<P>
Six Chinese cities -- Dalian, Shenzhen, Weihai, Xiamen, Zhuhai
and Zhangjiagang -- that are attending the POLMET '97 have done
equally well in both economic expansion and environment
protection, said Xie.
</P>
<P>
Xie outlined the aims in tackling water, air, solid waste, and
noise pollution in all 666 Chinese cities in the near future. By
the year of 2010, he said, sewage disposal plants would be built
in middle-sized cities, the air quality index would be reported on
a weekly or even daily basis, and non-lethal petrol would be used
in all automobiles. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
