<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share Prices Decline Sharply on Singapore Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, November 25 (Xinhua) -- Share prices declined
sharply on the Singapore market as the benchmark Straits Times
Industrials Index lost 35.45 points to close at 1,646.4 points
today.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said the sharp fall was triggered by steep losses in
Japan after the collapse of the Yamaichi Securities Co., the
fourth largest securities house of Japan.
</P>
<P>
However, they noted that talks of forced selling of Malaysian
shares also dampened sentiment for Singapore stocks.
</P>
<P>
The total market volume increased to 203.69 million units,
valued at 342.04 million Singapore dollars (about 213.78 million
US dollars). Declines overwhelmed advances by 290 to 61, while 267
other counters remained unchanged.
</P>
<P>
The Singapore Telecom was the most actively traded counter as
it registered a turnover of 19.36 million units. It was followed
by MBf Capital which had 18.37 million shares. Local computer
maker IPC Corporation had 10.76 million of its shares changed
hands.
</P>
<P>
Renong Bhd led the gainers of the day as it rose by 43 cents to
finish at 1.22 Singapore dollars. The Singapore Land increased by
20 cents to end at 4.6 Singapore dollars, while the Overseas Union
Bank (OUB) Foreign gained 15 cents to close at 5.85 Singapore
dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, Del Gro 500 was the biggest loser as it
declined by 4.1 dollars to end at three Singapore dollars.
Creative 50 fell by 2.3 dollars to close at 43.7 Singapore
dollars. Uniphoenix lost 1.6 dollars to finish at 2.42 Singapore
dollars, while the Singapore Press Holdings (SPH) Foreign was 1.3
dollars lower at 21.1 Singapore dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
