<HEADLINE> McRae Takes Comfortable Lead in RAC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, November 25 (Xinhua) -- Colin McRae of Britain took a
comfortable lead in British RAC auto rally after the third stage
of the final day in Cheltenham, England, on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
He was poised to win the race as his closest rival, fellow
countryman Richard Burns, suffered a puncture and lost five
minutes.
</P>
<P>
McRae would win this year's world title if he takes the RAC
race and title rival Tommi Makinen of Finland finishes out of the
top six. Makinen was now in the sixth place.
</P>
<P>
Burns, level overnight with McRae, set the fastest time on the
opening stage of the day in his Mitsubishi and maintained a
14-second lead heading into the 21st stage.
</P>
<P>
But Burns was forced to change one of the tires after a
puncture, which dropped him to fourth overall four minutes and 45
seconds off the lead.
</P>
<P>
McRae in his Subaru ended the stage two minutes and four
seconds ahead of Finn Juha Kankkunen in a Ford, with Ford teammate
Carlos Sainz of Spain third. 
</P>
</TEXT>
