<DOCNO> XIE19971125.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-25 10:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon's Two Leading Banks to Merge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, November 25 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Byblos Bank, one of
the country's largest banks, has agreed to a merger with Banque
Beyrouth pour le Commerce (BBC), a medium-sized bank, in a deal
rumored to be worth around 120 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
According to a press report said today, the move is the latest
in a series of central bank-sponsored consolidation in the
country's banking sector that has seen two other small banks
selling up to larger institutions.
</P>
<P>
The deal will result in a combined operation with a capital of
250 million U.S. dollars, and a market share of around 8 percent
of total deposits and 7.5 percent of loans, the Beirut Times
newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
An analyst told the paper that BBC did not wish to be left
behind by the big banks. "They did the smart thing by joining big
boys," he added.
</P>
<P>
Maurice Iskandar, director of Beirut-based rating agency Fins,
said smaller banks that incorporate into larger ones benefit from
services and technologies they find too expensive to develop on
their own.
</P>
<P>
The new bank, which retains the name Byblos, will become the
third largest bank in the country ahead of Banque Audi and behind
Banque du Liban et d'Outre-mer and Banque de la Mediterranee.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the need for size to spread the cost of investment
in technology and training, one of the main advantages of the deal
is BBC's 19-strong branch network, which according to analysts,
fits in well with Byblos's 33 outlets.
</P>
<P>
Sources familiar with the deal also say that Byblos is keen to
retain BBC personnel who will be represented on the combined
banks' board after the merger goes through.
</P>
<P>
Byblos's profits are expected to top 30 million U.S. dollars
this year and its market capitalization is estimated in excess of
600 million U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
