<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Plunge in Tokyo After Yamaichi Shock </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, November 25 (Xinhua) -- The collapse of Yamaichi
Securities Co. jolted the Tokyo stock market today, with the key
Nikkei index marking the second largest single-day loss for the
year.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei average of 225 selected issues on the First Section
of the Tokyo Stock Exchange plummeted 854.05 points, or 5.11
percent, from last Friday's close to 15,867.53.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
issues on the First Section, fell 65.06 points or 5.11 percent to
1,207.37.
</P>
<P>
Volume on the First Section came to an estimated 600 million
shares, slightly down from Friday's 606.32 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Failed Hokkaido Takushoku Bank was today's most actively traded
issues.
</P>
<P>
Following the news that Yamaichi filed Monday with the Finance
Ministry for voluntary closure of the 100-year-old company, market
participants rushed to sell issues, traders said.
</P>
<P>
On the Tokyo Foreign Exchange, the U.S. dollar was boosted by
Yamaichi's failure to the 128 yen level for the first time since
August 1992.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. currency momentarily touched a high of 128.07 yen just
after 3:30 p.m., surging from a low of 126.37 yen in the morning.
</P>
<P>
At 5 p.m., the dollar was quoted at 127.72-74 yen, up from
126.65-68 yen at 9 a.m. and from 126.85-95 yen late Monday in New
York.
</P>
<P>
The second largest single-day point loss for the year by the
Nikkei index encouraged players to sell the Japanese yen, dealers
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
