<HEADLINE> KDP Rejects Talks with PUK in Baghdad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, November 25 (Xinhua) -- A major Kurdish group has
refused to hold peace talks in Iraqi capital Baghdad with its
rival in northern Iraq, Turkey's Daily News reported today.
</P>
<P>
An official of the Kurdistan Democratic Party (KDP), who asked
not to be named, told the paper that his party made the decision
to protest the occupation of its positions by the pro-Iranian
Patriotic Union of Kurdistan (PUK).
</P>
<P>
However, the official expressed KDP's willingness to continue
the talks in Turkish capital Ankara. The KDP is reported to have
the backing of both Ankara and Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
The two contenders have been fighting for the control of
northern Iraq since the 1991 Gulf War when the Iraqi government
was rendered ineffective by the allied forces to exert influence
there.
</P>
<P>
The Baghdad government has been trying to mediate a peace deal
between the two sides, which held their first round of talks last
October in Baghdad under the auspices of Iraqi Deputy Prime
Minister Tariq Aziz, but made little progress.
</P>
<P>
A second round of talks was suspended because of the fierce
attacks launched by the KDP two weeks ago, in which it recaptured
most of the territories lost to the PUK.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Turkey, the United States and Britain have been
making efforts to realize reconciliation between the two parties,
and restore peace and stability in northern Iraq within a formula
of "Ankara Peace Process."
</P>
<P>
A KDP delegation led by its senior official Sami Abdurrahman
who is in charge of the peace talks with the PUK is in Ankara for
discussion with Turkish officials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
