<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Gov't to Postpone Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, November 25 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government has
decided to postpone investment implementation by two years due to
the monetary crisis, official sources from the Investment
Coordinating Board said here today.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made on Monday by State Minister of Investment
Sanyoto Sastrowardoyo, said the sources.
</P>
<P>
According to the state minister, the current monetary turmoil
does not affect investment approval but it delays implementation
of investment in the country.
</P>
<P>
According to investment regulations, investment application has
to be implemented in three years after being approved at the
latest.
</P>
<P>
Sastrowardoyo said the postponement aims at helping businessmen
who are facing liquidity problems and other difficulties due to
the monetary crisis.
</P>
<P>
Up till November 8, he said, approved domestic investment
amounted to 110 trillion rupiah (32.3 billion US dollars),
compared with 100.7 trillion (29.61 billions US dollars) of last
year. While the approved foreign investment totaled 29.6 billion
US dollars, compared with 29.9 billion dollars of last year.
</P>
<P>
The state minister said the implementation rate for domestic
investment was only 47.96 percent and the implementation rate for
foreign investment was 53.44 percent in the country.
</P>
<P>
The decline of investment implementation, he said, is due to
lack of liquidity while 90 percent of the approved investment is
financed with credit.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
