<HEADLINE> Egypt Summons Ambassador Amid Tensions With Qatar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, November 25 (Xinhua) -- Egypt has summoned its
ambassador to Qatar, Mohamed Meneissi, for consultations on the
growing strained relations with the small Gulf emirate, the Middle
East News Agency (MENA) reported today.
</P>
<P>
It was the second time in less than three weeks that the
ambassador was called back home. Angered by Qatar's insistence on
hosting the controversial fourth Middle East and North Africa
economic conference this month, Egypt recalled Meneissi on
November 7.
</P>
<P>
Egypt also has asked for an explanation from the Qatari
government regarding the statements its Foregin Minister Sheikh
Hamad ben Jassim ben Jabir al-Thani has recently made.
</P>
<P>
The Qatari official on November 12 linked Egypt to an attempted
coup against the Gulf Arab state's emir, Sheikh Hamad bin Khalifa
al-Thani, who toppled his father in a bloodless palace coup in
1995.
</P>
<P>
Cairo has denied Qatari allegations of involvement in the
failed coup in Qatar last year.
</P>
<P>
Egypt asked to know whether these statements express the
personal views of the Qatari official or mirror the official
conviction, said MENA.
</P>
<P>
Reports here said Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa met with
Qatari Ambassador to Egypt, Maniya al-Hagry, on Monday to lodge
the requests.
</P>
<P>
Moussa was reported to have told his ambassador to Doha early
this month that relations with Qatar would be kept at the least
possible levels so as not to adversely affect the always tense
inter-Arab relations.
</P>
<P>
The bilateral ties have deteriorated because of Egypt's boycott
of the Doha economic conference that involved Israel at a time
when the Middle East peace process remained deadlocked due to
Israel's hardline policy.
</P>
<P>
Egypt was also furious at a Qatari ban enacted last month
barring the entry of Egyptians and nationals of other nine
countries as a security precaution for the economic
conference. 
</P>
</TEXT>
