<DOCNO> XIE19971125.0175 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel's New Proposal Stirs Mixed Reactions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, November 25 (Xinhua) -- Reactions to Israel's
proposal on second-stage troop redeployment in the West Bank have
been mixed reactions and so far it seems hard for this proposal to
come into practice.
</P>
<P>
Worked out by Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's office here
on Monday, the proposal promises to transfer 6 to 8 percent of
West Bank to the Palestinian National Authority (PNA) and the
pullback would take place within five months.
</P>
<P>
But this is contingent on the PNA agreeing to suspend a
third-stage redeployment until the conclusion of final-status
talks.
</P>
<P>
In effect, this means that the third pullback would demarcate
the final boundary line of the Palestinian entity. Upon
completion of the second-stage redeployment, the PNA would control
35 percent to 37 percent of West Bank. At present it has only 29
percent of the land under its rule.
</P>
<P>
Late Monday night, Netanyahu's legal advisor Yitzhak Molcho met
with PNA Chairman Yasser Arafat in Gaza Strip in an attempt to
convince him to agree to Netanyahu's redeployment plan, but
Arafat said "no."
</P>
<P>
The other PNA officials reacted on Monday that they believe
Netanyahu is not serious about pulling back Israeli troops.
</P>
<P>
PNA local Affairs Minister Saeb Erekat said 90 percent of the
West Bank should be transferred to the PNA by the time the parties
approach final-status talks, and the PNA adheres to the original
Oslo timetable.
</P>
<P>
Israel has contended that intervening acts of terrorism delayed
the implementation.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian Legislative Council Speaker Abu Ala echoed Erekat's
statement, saying that he expected Israel to pull back from 90
percent of the land, 30 percent in each stage. Otherwise, he said,
the Palestinians would not agree to begin negotiations on a
permanent peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
Within Israel's coalition government, Netanyahu's proposal
received strong support from his key cabinet ministers like
Foreign Minister David Levy, Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai,
Infrastructure Minister Ariel Sharon, Agriculture Minister Rafael
Eitan and Interior Minister Eli Suissa.
</P>
<P>
They conditioned implementation of the pullbacks on a genuine
PNA crackdown on terrorism.
</P>
<P>
The Third Way also supports this proposal. But some right-wing
lawmakers, including Michael Kleiner representing the Land of
Israel Front in parliament, oppose this proposal, threatening to
topple Netanyahu's government should the second-stage pullback be
carried out.
</P>
<P>
Cabinet Secretary Danny Naveh and Netanyahu's Policy Advisor
Uzi Arad will travel to Cairo today to present the proposal to
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak in a bid to obtain Egypt's
endorsement, so that Mubarak can persuade the Palestinians to
accept the plan.
</P>
<P>
Under the Hebron Agreement signed January this year, Israel had
to complete its first-stage and second-stage troop redeployments
in West Bank by March 5 and September 7 respectively, and the
third-stage redeployment must be completed by August of 1998.
</P>
<P>
But so far no official redeployment has been executed due to
the Palestinian-Israel quarrel over the size of pullout and
terrorist bombing attacks in Jerusalem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971125.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SKorea Eyes Cutbacks in Foreign Exchange Expenditure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, November 25 (Xinhua) -- South Koreans, civic groups and
the governments are now launching campaigns on cutting foreign
exchange spending in a bid to help the country out of the current
financial difficulties.
</P>
<P>
According to the Ministry of Finance and Economy (MOFE), among
this year's approximately 14-billion-U.S. dollar current-account,
the invisible trade shortfall mainly for overseas travel, expected
to reach 8 billion dollars, will be blamed for worsening the
nation's international balance of payment position.
</P>
<P>
Civic groups have called on the public to refrain from making
unnecessary overseas trips and to deposit dollars into banks, as
well as buy South Korean products.
</P>
<P>
Such civic group members can be seen in parks and on streets,
appealing to the people to be thrifty and save hard currency so
that the nation can get out of the financial dilemma.
</P>
<P>
Media reports said many South Koreans have decided to delay
their overseas trips until after the crisis and travel agencies
said more customers asked to cancel their overseas tours while
some of them turned to domestic ones.
</P>
<P>
The government stands poised to come up with a package of
measures aimed at reducing the country's invisible trade deficit.
</P>
<P>
First, the MOFE urged government agencies to cut officials'
business trips as a way to preserve hard currency.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the government seeks to put the brakes on lavish
travel expenses. Specifically, monitoring on overseas credit-card
expenses will be strengthened.
</P>
<P>
Under the plan, those spending more than 5,000 dollars overseas
with credit cards will be subjet to intensive investigations and
face punishment if their expenses violate foreign exchange
regulations. Possible violations include spending on gambling or
excessive payments for shopping. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
