<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-25 09:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank: PNA Has Great Economic Potential </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, November 25 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinian economy can
grow even under conditions of closure by Israel, The Jerusalem
Post said today, quoting a World Bank report.
</P>
<P>
The report, entitled "Development Under Adversity: The
Palestinian Economy in Transition" and issued Monday, said this
was achieved by taking advantage of its favorable trading status
with the U.S. and European Union,
</P>
<P>
Noting the stifling effects of Israeli blockade of the West
Bank and Gaza Strip, the report finds there are ways that the
Palestinian National Authority (PNA) can take economic matters
into its own hands before a diplomatic solution comes about.
</P>
<P>
Among its main recommendations are: increasing the
diversification of trade, especially given the PNA's favorable
trading status with the U.S. and European Union; spending more
government funds on building infrastructure; fostering more
competition within the Palestinian economy.
</P>
<P>
Joseph Stiglitz, the Bank's chief economist, said the
Palestinian economy had enormous potential, citing that students
in Palestinian self-rule areas attend school for an average of
8.1 years, which is close to the Israeli figure.
</P>
<P>
He added that compared to many other economies, the PNA has
considerable capital at its disposal and a rich set of
Palestinian non-governmental organizations around world, which can
push forward the self-rule economy dramatically.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank report also outlines hardships faced by
Palestinians during Israeli occupation, and the uncertainties of
the interim period.
</P>
<P>
"The transitional arrangement has created an awkward mismatch
between responsibility and authority for the PNA," the report
said. "While the PNA can license a business in West Bank or Gaza,
it is Israel that largely controls the movement of goods and
people, including workers and managers."
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, the report continues, the self-rule areas are
split into separate economic units. Transport between the north
and south of West Bank is "hampered by the Jerusalem bottleneck."
</P>
<P>
Palestinian and the United Nations estimates put the annual
cost of a prolonged closure imposed by Israel at 1.825 billion to
2.555 billion U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
