<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian MP Bombarded for Her Political Will Stunt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, November 25 (Xinhua) -- Bizarre, weird, stupid,
unwise, nutty, irresponsible are some of the terms used today by
Australian leading politicians to comment on Australian MP Pauline
Hanson's move to have her will taped under alleged death threats.
</P>
<P>
Her move, which was disclosed today, drew sharp attacks from
Australian Prime Minister John Howard, Deputy Prime Minister Tim
Fischer, Foreign Minister Alexander Downer and other leading
politicians.
</P>
<P>
Hanson, who is at the center of a race debate in Australia
sparked by her anti-Asian immigration and anti-indigenous people
speech last year, has her last political will and testament
recorded in an address to the nation to be broadcast fully only in
the event that she is assassinated.
</P>
<P>
During her will, Hanson says: "Fellow Australians, if you are
seeing me now, it means I've been murdered," the country's leading
newspaper The Australian reported today.
</P>
<P>
"For the sake of our children and our children's children, you
must fight on ... do not let my passing distract you for one
moment", Hanson was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
But excerpts from her 12-minute will is to be screened tonight
by Channel Seven, a national TV station.
</P>
<P>
Her move was prompted by a flood of death threats she claimed
she had received since founding her One Nation Party in April this
year, Channel Seven said.
</P>
<P>
She denied the address to the nation was a stunt in the wake of
her party's slump to three percent in the polls.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister John Howard, who is now in Vancouver for the
Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation meeting, expressed surprise over
Hanson's move, the Australian Associated Press (AAP) reported.
</P>
<P>
"It seems very weird to me," the prime minister said.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Prime Minister Tim Fischer today told MPs that the
taping of a video will by Pauline Hanson was one of the most
irresponsible actions by any member of parliament that he could
remember.
</P>
<P>
Fischer told a joint meeting of Liberal and National MPs that
Hanson had breached a long-standing convention against bringing
the public's attention to death threats against politicians.
</P>
<P>
The bizarre twist given to the death threats by the recording
of the video will was a desperate attempt to generate publicity by
the Member of Oxley, he said.
</P>
<P>
Asked about Hanson's will, Foreign Minister Alexander Downer
said, "I would say it sounds a bit nutty," AAP reported.
</P>
<P>
Opposition Leader Kim Beazley described Hanson's video message
as totally bizarre.
</P>
<P>
"It is the case that from time to time those of us in politics
face a death threat or face threats to our security. But
generally, politicians considered it wise not to talk about
threats," he said.
</P>
<P>
"This goes a bit beyond that - this is truly bizarre behavior,"
Beazley said.
</P>
<P>
Jeff Kennett, premier of the state of Victoria, said Hanson was
"bizarre" and "stupid" by having her will recorded.
</P>
<P>
"I thought it was bizarre, but then again everything about
Pauline Hanson is absolutely bizarre," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971125.0187 </DOCNO>
