<HEADLINE> Providing Home For Endangered Animals In China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, November 25 (Xinhua) -- A six-month old red-crowned
crane has become a new member of the endangered animal species
center at the Tianjin Zoo, in this largest port city in north
China.
</P>
<P>
The crane is one of a dozen endangered animals that are sent to
the center for medical treatment each year.
</P>
<P>
Since its establishment in 1994, the center has bred rare
animals like giraffes, Siberian tigers, pandas, and jaguars, and
800 rare animals.
</P>
<P>
The center has also set up a zoology development and
consultation center and forged close cooperative relations with
zoos in Japan, the United States, the Netherlands, and Britain.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
