<HEADLINE> Multinational Firms Renew Confidence in Malaysia's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, November 25 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia-based
multinational companies today renewed their confidence in the
Malaysian economy following a special briefing here by the
country's Deputy Prime Minister Anwar Ibrahim who is also finance
minister.
</P>
<P>
Some 120 chief executive officers and top executives from 80
multinational companies, including American ones, got first-hand
information from the briefing on steps taken to address the
country's economic problems following the depreciation of the
ringgit and the plunge in share prices, U.S. Ambassador John
Malott to Malaysia told reporters after the briefing.
</P>
<P>
"He (Anwar) has done a wonderful job in raising the confidence
of everyone in the room," Malott said. "We are confident in the
way the country is managing the problem as well as in him (Anwar)
as the finance minister."
</P>
<P>
Malott said the briefing covered a broad range of issues
including the currency and stock market setbacks and the
International Monetary Fund's role in helping economic recovery in
South Korea, Thailand and Indonesia. 
</P>
