<DOCNO> XIE19971125.0192 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Share Market Falters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, November 25 (Xinhua) -- Falls in Asian stock markets
dragged the local exchange lower today but strong buying in the
afternoon ensured it finished well off its lows.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index closed down 27.7 points at 2454.4,
well above its intra-day low of 2432.0.
</P>
<P>
The market was driven lower in the mid-session on fears of a
major collapse on Asian exchanges following Friday's failure of
major Japanese brokerage Yamaichi Securities and was down over two
percent at one stage.
</P>
<P>
But the lower prices prompted renewed support and a wave of
value buying in the afternoon revived flagging stocks.
</P>
<P>
The value of shares traded again broke 1 billion Australian
dollars (687.1 million U.S. dollars) with just under 1.25 billion
Australian dollars (858.8 million U.S. dollars) worth of shares
turned over on volume of 397.85 million shares. Falling stocks
outnumbered rising stocks by 764 to 347.
</P>
<P>
Telstra topped trade as 47.37 million installment receipts
changed hands worth 85.47 million U.S. dollars. The receipts
dropped three cents to 2.64 Australian dollars in line with the
general market fall.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index lost 40.2 points to 4186.6 and all
resources index shed 18.4 points to 1075.4.
</P>
<P>
National Australia Bank shed 53 cents to 19.28 Australian
dollars, ANZ bank lost 17 cents to 9.88 Australian dollars,
Westpac bank eased eight cents to 9.04 Australian dollars on
turnover of 9.3 million shares and Commonwealth dropped 17 cents
to 17.30 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Resources Leader BHP also fell 25 cents to 13.40 Australian
dollars and global giant Rio Tinto lost 12.7 cents to 16.45
Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The gold index lost 24.2 points at 922.4 as gold bullion lost
2.15 U.S. dollars from Monday's close to trade at 302.75 U,S.
dollars an ounce. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
