<DOCNO> XIE19971125.0195 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepali Currency Further Devalued </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, November 25 (Xinhua) -- The Nepali rupee devalued
again today, the second time in a week, after the India rupee fell
against the dollar.
</P>
<P>
The Nepal Rastra Bank (NRB) today refixed the buying and
selling rates of the dollar at 60.26 rupees and 60.86 rupees
respectively from Monday's 59.75 rupees and 60.35 rupees.
</P>
<P>
Since the Indian rupee fell to a two-year low against the
dollar Monday due to the country's deepening political crisis, the
Nepali rupee, which is pegged to the Indian rupee at a fixed rate
of 1.6:1, has no other choice but to follow suit.
</P>
<P>
But the NRB, the country's central bank, did not intervene in
the market this time, as the market has adequate foreign exchange
reserves, Nepali newspapers said.
</P>
<P>
When the Nepali rupee fell against the greenback a week ago,
the NRB floated 13.5 million U.S. dollars to prop up the currency.
</P>
<P>
Since August 27, the Nepali rupee has devalued five times, and
the NRB has intervened in the market three times by floating 44.1
million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Foreign reserves held by the NRB had reached about 809 million
dollars by mid-July, the NRB said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
