<DOCNO> XIE19971125.0196 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Provides $77 Million for Lake Victoria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, November 25 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank has set aside
77 million U.S. Dollars for the first phase of a five-year Lake
Victoria environmental management program, the East African
Standard today quoted a bank official as saying.
</P>
<P>
Graeme Donovan, World Bank's Principal Economist in charge of
agriculture operations in eastern and southern Africa, told the
paper that the money would be used for research purposes.
</P>
<P>
The research will focus on fisheries, water quality in the
lake, management of the wetlands and the control of its
degradation through various environmental factors, he added.
</P>
<P>
Donovan was on a fact-finding mission last week in Kisumu,
west Kenya, where he met Nyanza Provincial Commissioner Wilson
Chepkwony before proceeding to Uganda and later Tanzania for
similar missions.
</P>
<P>
He noted that following a tripartite agreement among the three
east African countries of Kenya, Uganda and Tanzania on the Lake
Victoria Environmental Management Project (LVEMP) last year,
funds had now been released for the project.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 3,000 hectares of the lake is covered by the fast
growing weed of hyacinth which has negated efforts for effective
fisheries and transport, and interfered with the flora and fauna
in the lake.
</P>
<P>
On Kenya's side, the Kisumu Pier is currently closed for both
cargo and passenger transport because of the weed, and several
beaches are completely blocked for transport.
</P>
<P>
Donovan pointed out that 25 million Dollars had been allocated
to Kenya for the initial phase of the five-year project.
</P>
<P>
He said that mechanical removal of the weed is the first step
and later on followed by using biological methods, adding that
the World Bank is committed to the project's success. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
