<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lower Reaches Of Yellow River Have Water Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, November 25 (Xinhua) -- The lower reaches of the
Yellow River ended a 220-day dry spell on November 21 after a dry
season and increased water use by industry and agriculture led to
drying up along parts of the river.
</P>
<P>
The situation had gotten very serious this year, and parts of
Shandong Province, where people rely on Yellow River water for
industry, agriculture, and daily use, were having a crisis.
</P>
<P>
By November, several tens of thousands of people had difficulty
obtaining drinking water. In some areas there was little water
left and the water in stock could only last until mid-November,
said local sources.
</P>
<P>
The China National Flood and Drought Prevention General
Headquarters issued an emergency circular early this month calling
for more water discharged from reservoirs on the upper reaches of
the Yellow River and an effort was made by central departments,
water conservation organizations, and provinces and autonomous
region.
</P>
<P>
This was the fourth such actions have been taken this year.
</P>
<P>
Reservoirs at Sanmenxia and Liujiaxia have increased the amount
of water discharged, and Henan, Shaanxi, and Shanxi provinces, the
Ningxia Hui and Inner Mongolia autonomous regions have reduced the
amount of water being taken from the river for industrial and
agricultural use. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
