<HEADLINE> Motorcycles Popular In Southern Chinese City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, November 25 (Xinhua) -- The 250,000 motorcycles in
Shantou, in south China's Guangdong Province, have become the
major means of transportation.
</P>
<P>
According to a Bureau of Urban Construction official, the 1.07
million people living in the city's urban area own 180,000
motorcycles.
</P>
<P>
One woman who works as an accountant said that common people in
Shantou can afford motorcycles since an expensive one costs 70,000
to 80,000 yuan, and an ordinary one around 30,000 yuan.
</P>
<P>
Most parking lots in the city are now controlled by
motorcycles, which also cause jams on major roads during rush
hours.
</P>
<P>
The popularity of motorcycles has resulted in less use of
public transportation. Statistics show only 150 buses in the city,
while in most Chinese cities there are 7 buses for every 10,000
people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971125.0202 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Government Pays For Education In China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, November 25 (Xinhua) -- It is governments at various
levels, instead of the society, that provide financing for the
country's education, according a senior Chinese official in charge
of education.
</P>
<P>
"Central and local governments always take education input as
the key to education development," said Chen Zhili, vice-minister
in charge of the State Education Commission (SEC), at a national
conference on education reforms that was held recently in
Changsha, the capital of central China's Hunan Province.
</P>
<P>
Chen said that it is a mistake to think that most of China's
education funding comes from donations. "The government remains
the major patron for education," he added.
</P>
<P>
Latest statistics showed that in 1996 China spent over 226
billion yuan on education, and 167.17 billion yuan of that came
from state revenues, making nearly 74 percent of the whole
education expenditures.
</P>
<P>
China supports education by getting funds from various sectors,
a change from the past when the government was the sole backer of
the national education system.
</P>
<P>
Changsha, for example, has built 107 primary schools with
Project Hope funds and 218 special schools with 20 million yuan
(about 2.4 million US dollars) in donations over the past decade.
</P>
<P>
Project Hope was begun in 1989 and is the largest education
foundation to help dropouts return to school. It also helps build
primary schools and libraries with donations from China and abroad.
</P>
<P>
Changsha has also raised some 1.5 billion yuan from the public
during the past decade, but this is peanuts compared to government
appropriations for education, according to an official of the
Changsha City Government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971125.0203 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN Urged to Remain Cohesive to Face Common </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, November 25 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Foreign
Minister Abdullah Ahmad Badawi today stressed the need for ASEAN
to remain cohesive when taking the initiative in addressing common
challenges that affect the region.
</P>
<P>
As ASEAN stands at the threshold of the 21st century, it is
confronted with the challenges of ensuring its dynamism and
relevance in a rapidly changing global socio-economic and
political environment, he said when opening an International
Conference on ASEAN at the Crossroads: Opportunities and
Challenges here.
</P>
<P>
Economically, he said, "The current financial and currency
turmoils that we face now bear testimony to these daunting
challenges for us to reinforce our resolve and strengthen our
political will for closer regional cooperation."
</P>
<P>
The contagion effect of the crisis has shown that no economy,
however strong, can be immune to the economic conditions in the
neighborhood, he said, adding it is therefore "not good enough" to
put one's own house in order if the neighboring economies are in
disarray and hence it is important to have regional approaches to
complement national efforts.
</P>
<P>
He said in the political, security and strategic areas, the
security environment in Southeast Asia and the wider Asia Pacific
region is "generally stable and peaceful" and the challenge for
ASEAN member countries is to entrench the positive security
environment so that economic development could continue to be the
main focus for countries in the region.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the future of the region will depend very
much on how well and how quickly the economies of the members are
transformed into market-oriented ones and are simultaneously
integrated into the ASEAN Free Trade Area (AFTA) arrangement as
well as on how well they can adjust to the ASEAN way and on how
prepared the original ASEAN countries are in accommodating and
leading them.
</P>
<P>
He said that with the determination, commitment and maturity of
past and present ASEAN leaders, ASEAN has grown from strength to
strength and has succeeded in most of its endeavors over the last
three decades.
</P>
<P>
"ASEAN is slowly emerging as one of the centers in the
evolution of an emerging multipolar order," he added.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN groups Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia, Myanmar, Laos, the
Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
Some 40 experts from all ASEAN members except Vietnam and from
Canada and Germany are attending the two-day international
conference themed "ASEAN Challenges and Opportunities" jointly
organized by the Malaysian Institute of Economic Research and
Germany's Konrad Adenauer Foundation.
</P>
<P>
At the conference, the participants will deliberate mainly
currency crisis, the geopolitical and security challenges, the
economic challenges and ASEAN external economic relations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
