<HEADLINE> Australia Aids Drought-hit Indonesian Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, November 25 (Xinhua) -- Australia today promised one
million Australian dollars (700,000 U.S. dollars) in drought aid
for the Indonesian province of Irian Jaya.
</P>
<P>
Australian Foreign Minister Alexander Downer said half of
Australia's donation would go to a United Nations Department of
Humanitarian Affairs (UNDHA) appeal and the other half to the
International Committee of the Red Cross.
</P>
<P>
He said 400,000 people faced starvation in Irian Jaya, which
borders Papua New Guinea where 500,000 people are also at risk
because of severe drought.
</P>
<P>
"A UN (United Nations) disaster assessment team which recently
visited the worst affected areas found Irian Jaya is on the verge
of famine," Downer said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"Smoke from forest fires is severely restricting flights
carrying food into the affected regions," he noted.
</P>
<P>
"The team also reported that local water supplies are drying
out and the little water left is polluted resulting in more people
suffering diarrhea, scabies and respiratory tract infections,"
the foreign minister said.
</P>
<P>
Australia has already donated 4.9 million U.S. dollars towards
drought relief in Papua New Guinea, while 2.1 million U.S. dollars
has now been committed to Indonesia for drought and forest fire
assistance.  
</P>
</TEXT>
