<HEADLINE> COMESA Urged to Lift Sanctions on Burundi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, November 25 (Xinhua) -- The Common Market for Eastern
and Southern Africa (COMESA) has been urged to lift sanctions
against Burundi because the sanctions are hurting the interests
of the business community in the region.
</P>
<P>
Boney Katatumba, chairman of the Eastern and Southern Africa
Business Organization (ESABO), made the appeal here Monday when
he addressed the fourth meeting of the COMESA Council of
Ministers.
</P>
<P>
He noted that while COMESA countries are effecting the
sanctions, European, American and Asian business communities have
taken advantage of the vacuum to flood it with goods.
</P>
<P>
Katatumba warned that if the situation is allowed to continue
unchecked, the Burundi market could be lost for forever.
</P>
<P>
"We fear that by the time the economic embargo on Burundi is
lifted, we would have lost the market to our competitors. We
therefore appeal to the Council of Ministers to consider
alternative measures to deal with the Burundi issues." he said.
</P>
<P>
After Burundi military leader Pierre Buyoya took power from
civilian president Sylvestre Ntibantunganya in a military coup in
July last year, the sanctions were imposed to force him to
restore democracy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
