<HEADLINE> Yamaichi's Singapore Units to Wind Down Operations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, November 25 (Xinhua) -- The three Singapore
subsidiaries of the troubled Yamaichi Securities Co. will be
voluntarily winding down their operations after the fourth largest
securities house of Japan collapsed Monday.
</P>
<P>
The three Singapore units are engaged in the securities,
futures and merchant banking operations and each of them is a
separate legal entity from Yamaichi Securities Co. in Japan, local
industrial sources said today.
</P>
<P>
A Monetary Authority of Singapore (MAS) spokesman has said that
the MAS, the central bank, is in close contact with Yamaichi
regarding their operations in Singapore.
</P>
<P>
The three units -- the Yamaichi Merchant Bank, Yamaichi
futures, and Yamaichi Securities (Singapore), said that all their
liabilities will be met since they had sufficient assets to do so,
but some 130 employees will lose their jobs.
</P>
<P>
A Business Times report said that it was still not certain how
long the winding-down process will take, but it is likely to go on
for a few months.
</P>
<P>
As for other Yamaichi companies in Singapore, which include
Yamaichi Asia Venture Capital and Yamaichi Research Institute, the
report said that it was not clear what will happen to them. But
Yamaichi Capital Management, which operates independently of
Yamaichi Securities in Japan, emphasized that it is maintaining
normal operations here.  
</P>
</TEXT>
