<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Illegal Firearms Proliferated in S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, November 25 (Xinhua) -- More than 200,000 legal
firearms had been reported lost or stolen in South Africa in the
past four years, local daily the Citizen reported today.
</P>
<P>
All these guns have added to the proliferation of illegals
firearms, which increased violent crime in the country, Ricde
Caris, director of police legal services, was quoted as saying at
a one-day seminar on arms control and disarmament.
</P>
<P>
Caris said the whole attitude of South Africans regarding
firearms was wrong, with people believing they could secure their
lives by arming themselves.
</P>
<P>
South Africans had to learn that possessing firearms did not
guarantee their safety, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Jenni Irish, director of KwaZulu Natal-based Network of
Independent Monitors, said there was a thin line dividing
licensed and unlicensed guns as "a licensed gun today could be an
unlicensed gun tomorrow," due to negligence and theft.
</P>
<P>
She said the proliferation of illegal weapons contributed
significantly to the cyclical problem where "gun breed guns" in a
race in which different groups sought to enhance their fire
capacity either defensively or offensively.
</P>
<P>
South Africa has been troubled with the proliferation of
illegal weapons for years, which have seen increasing death and
injuries in armed robberies throughout the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971125.0210 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ancient Canal Discovered In East Chinese City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, November 25 (Xinhua) -- The remains of an ancient
canal were discovered recently at a construction site in the city
of Zhenjiang in east China's Jiangsu province.
</P>
<P>
Archaeologists say that the Chuancheng Canal, which lies in a
north-south direction, was built no later than the Eastern Jin
Dynasty (317-420 A.D.), and 700 years later, a new canal was dug
to the west, running parallel to the first.
</P>
<P>
A number of relics, including a porcelain dog and a pottery
mould for baking, dating back as much as 1,500 years, were found
near the canal, as well as 52 bowls and pots, on the bottom of
which there are characters in ink, giving lists of food, surnames,
and official titles.  
</P>
</TEXT>
