in Eastern Slavonia, the last Serb-controlled part of Croatia, for
nine months after the U.N. administration leaves, Croatian Deputy
Foreign Minister Ivo Sanader Monday said.
</P>
<P>
The Croatian government also suggested that some 180 U.N.
policemen be stationed as observers in the region. The mandate of
the current U.N. administration is due to expire on January 15,
after which control of the region should pass to Croatia in
accordance with a 1995 peace accord. (Croatia-Serbs) 
