<HEADLINE> Radio Units Offered to Track Rhinos in Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, November 25 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania's Mkomazi
Reserve has received 29 two-way radion systems from a British
Africa early this month, "The Guardian" said today.
</P>
<P>
The GP-900 Motorola radio systems would enable game wardens
to make quick response if the rhinos are found in a difficult
situation.
</P>
<P>
Tony Fitzjohn, the field director for the Mkomazi Project,
said that the reserve is located in a remote and largely
inaccessible area, covering 3,500 square kilometers.
</P>
<P>
"When talking of such distances, it is essential to be able
to communicate with your team#," he said.
</P>
<P>
When poachers are sighted on the reserves the two-way radio
will ensure fast communication and a prompt call to action, even
in the most isolated areas, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
No more than 10,500 rhinos are left in the wild in the world
today, while poaching continues to be a threat, according to the
report. Tanzania has between 20 and 25 black rhions left, the
wildlife authorities said.
</P>
<P>
The four black rhinos were the first of a total of 10
expected to be transferred from South Africa to Tanzania in the
coming six months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
