<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Oldest City Wall Found In Central China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, November 25 (Xinhua) -- A city wall dating back at
least 6,000 years has been discovered in Lixian county in central
China's Hunan Province.
</P>
<P>
The ancient wall is made of beaten earth, two meters high and
10 meters wide at the base, and according to scientists, it is the
oldest city wall ever found in the country.
</P>
<P>
Archaeologists from the Hunan Provincial Institute of
Archaeology studied the site for more than a month earlier this
year and found that the the city wall had been rebuilt three times
long ago.
</P>
<P>
The first time was about 5,500 years ago, when part of the
city's moat was filled in. The second was about 200 years later,
when the wall was widened. In the latest reconstruction some 4,800
years ago, the wall was further widened to 37 m. at the base and
13 m. at the top.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
