<HEADLINE> Operation Olympia Deals Heavy Blow to Ndrangheta </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, November 24 (Xinhua) -- The third stage of Operation
Olympia, the two-year investigation against the Calabrian crime
syndicate `Ndrangheta', has dealt a heavy blow to organized crime
in Italy's southernmost area, ANSA News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
A major police operation during the night saw the arrest of 72
people on charges of racketeering, murder, extortion and
loan-sharking, and about 29 have already been incarcerated, ANSA
quoted police source as saying.
</P>
<P>
Operation Olympia has brought 376 people to trial over the past
two years and another 185 are in the appeals court.
</P>
<P>
among those arrested was Giuseppe Aquila, 36, vice-president of
the province of Reggio Calabria and a local leader of the Froza
Italian party.
</P>
<P>
The Ndrangheta was defined by Pier Luigi Vigna, the current
national anti-mafia prosecutor, as the most "lethal" among Italy's
organized crime syndicates, with branches throughout Italy and
abroad.
</P>
<P>
Two years of investigation gave authorities a clear picture of
how Ndrangheta works, where it gets its money and the aggressive
strategies of the gangs, the arms suppliers and contacts in
international drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
The Ndrangheta's biggest source of income, however, comes
mainly from drug trafficking. Its newest market is in eastern
Europe where it is also able to buy heavy weapons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
