<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> California Sets up Special Courts for Domestic Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, November 24 (Xinhua) -- California, the most
populous state in the United States, has set up a new kind of
court to help abused women.
</P>
<P>
There are 12 such domestic violence courts in the state, where
family support projects, probation departments, district
attorney's offices and public defenders coordinate services and
work together to make it harder for offenders to elude the system.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that as many as four million women in the United
States suffer from some kind of violence at the hands of their
husbands or boyfriends each year. The Department of Justice
estimated in 1995 that each year women were the victims of more
than 4.5 million violent crimes. Victims of domestic violence come
from all walks of life, cultures, income groups and religions.
</P>
<P>
In California, previously domestic violence cases would go from
one courtroom to another, sometimes dragging on for a year. The
"family affairs" often make it difficult for law enforcement
agencies. Usually defendants who are arrested and brought to court
have been abusing their partners for a long time. On the other
hand, victims often intercede for the defendants, asking for
restraining orders to be rescinded and cases to be dismissed.
</P>
<P>
This could eventually lead to serious consequences. This past
August, a northern California county court dismissed a battery
charge against a man called James Nivette, a 54-year-old
psychologist. His girlfriend Gina Barnett, the victim, refused to
testify. Last week the man was apprehended in France on suspicion
of murdering Barnett.
</P>
<P>
Now with the special court, there is continual monitoring and
consistent follow-up, because the same judge, public defender,
district attorney and probation officer deal with one domestic
violence case after another.
</P>
<P>
If a defendant pleads guilty, he must admit to the judge what
he did wrong. This admission is the key because he has to own up
to his violent tendencies in the mandatory counseling program,
according to the judges.
</P>
<P>
Practices vary from court to court. But usually a conviction
for first-time offenders calls for three years' probation and up
to 30 days in jail. In the first year of probation, attendance in
a violence prevention program is required. Two weeks after the
plea, the offender must report back to court and show proof that
he enrolled in the classes. If he doesn't enroll, he could be sent
to jail. 30 days later, he must return to court with a progress
report from the program. After the first progress report, if the
offender is doing well, the judge will ask him to check back with
the court every 60 days. Between court visits, probation officers
randomly visit group counseling sessions to monitor his progress.
</P>
<P>
The new kind of court was pioneered in 1993 in San Diego,
California's second largest city, where coordinated domestic
violence intervention and prevention work has been recognized as a
national model. In 1989, a coalition of over 200 people
representing some 40 agencies formed the San Diego Domestic
Violence Task Force. The task force continues its work today in
the form of San Diego Domestic Violence Council, Inc. As a result
of its work, specialized domestic violence units have been
established in the attorney offices, the probation department and
the city police department. With more than 30 detectives,
sergeants and volunteer personnel, the San Diego Police Department
has one of the largest specialized domestic violence units of any
major law enforcement agencies in the United States.
</P>
<P>
But the San Diego Domestic Violence Council said last week that
the city has become a victim of its own success. "After 10 years
of declining domestic violence homicides, the rate has increased
40 percent this year," it said. The council has recently called
for more prevention efforts in cooperation with school,
businesses, medical professionals and churches, and for ways to
make the victims safer and hold abusers accountable.
</P>
<P>
Many laws have been made and many organizations set up in the
United States to deal with domestic violence. Hundreds of books
have also been written about the subject (The University of
Washington alone lists 184 such books on the Internet). But the
problem is still there and women continue to be victimized. One
district attorney in San Francisco said that the unique problem in
domestic violence cases is dealing with people who in most
instances will continue to live together. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971125.0233 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World's Highest Hydro-Electric Power Plant Goes Operational </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, November 25 (Xinhua) -- The Jiagang Hydro-electric Power
