<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Astronauts Aboard Columbia Capture Satellite </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 24 (Xinhua) -- Two space-walking
astronauts from Shuttle Columbia grabbed the out-of-control
science satellite, Spartan, and brought it back to the spacecraft
Monday night.
</P>
<P>
Having waited for more than an hour for the satellite to tilt
the right way, American astronaut Winston Scott and Japanese
astronaut Takao Doi leaned over and grasped opposite ends of the
slowly spinning satellite with their gloved hands and pulled it
back to the craft.
</P>
<P>
The work in the first stage went smoothly while the craft was
flying over the Pacific Ocean at around 21:00 p.m. (0200 GMT
Tuesday).
</P>
<P>
However, the astronauts could not lower the satellite into its
cradle in the cargo bay. So Mission Control ordered the crew to
use the shuttle's robot arm to help them.
</P>
<P>
The two space-walking astronauts floated out the hatch of
Columbia at 19:16 p.m. (0016 GMT Tuesday) as the shuttle closed in
on the satellite, floating 290 kilometers above Earth.
</P>
<P>
The 10 million U.S. dollar satellite was released on Friday. It
was intended to conduct research on the sun, but for reasons that
are still unclear, it malfunctioned within moments of its release.
</P>
<P>
While the crew on Columbia tried to retrieve it with the
shuttle's robot arm, it started tumbling too quickly to be grabbed
safely. The spaceship then backed away.
</P>
<P>
After three days of separation and one hour into the spacewalk,
Columbia was back at Spartan's side. By then, Scott and Doi had
positioned themselves on opposite ends of a platform spanning the
cargo bay, their feet in restraints and their bodies leaning back
to avoid being struck by the 1.5-ton satellite.
</P>
<P>
Ground controllers planned a series of checks to determine
whether it might be feasible to send the satellite back out later
this week.
</P>
<P>
In 1992, three space walkers captured with their gloved hands a
slowly spinning communications satellite, which was three times
the size of Spartan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
