<HEADLINE> Largest Tibetan Pagoda Takes on New Look </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 25 (Xinhua) -- Beijing residents can now
visit a renovated version of the largest and oldest Tibetan
Buddhist pagoda in China, after the completion of a refurbishing
program.
</P>
<P>
The 57.9-meter tall White Pagoda in Beijing's Xicheng District
was built in 1279 (Yuan Dynasty) with the White Pagoda Temple. It
is somewhat difficult to be seen from the street because of the
high buildings that have been built around it since the late 1960s.
</P>
<P>
To increase tourism in the district, the Xicheng District
Government collected more than 30 million yuan (3.5 million US
dollars) earlier this year to renovate the pagoda, which is ten
meters taller than the Tibetan pagoda in Beihai Park.
</P>
<P>
The project meant the removal a 2,000-sq.m. grocery store and
39 families from around the pagoda and the pulling down of
several structures, which prevented people from seeing the
pagoda. 
</P>
</TEXT>
