<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Half of Bangladeshis Feared Infected With TB Virus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, November 25 (Xinhua) -- More than 50 percent of the
people in Bangladesh may have been infected with tuberculosis
bacteria while at least 350,000 others get infected every year,
the World Health Organization (WHO) said in a report released here
today.
</P>
<P>
"It is likely that over half of 120 million Bangladeshis are
already infected with TB bacteria," said the report published by a
visiting WHO experts team.
</P>
<P>
It added that the directly observed treatment, short-course
(DOTS) method is the most effective weapon against the epidemic.
</P>
<P>
The WHO team, which has visited nearly 100 TB control projects
in the country over the last two weeks, noted that 80 percent of
the TB patients are being cured where the DOTS method is applied.
</P>
<P>
The field-level introduction of the DOTS strategy began four
years ago in four counties in this poor South Asian country. Now,
the method is in use in 363 counties and nearly 30,000 health
workers have so far received training in various aspects of the
DOTS strategy.
</P>
<P>
The projects have received support from the World Bank and the
government of the Netherlands while the WHO is providing technical
assistance.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
