<HEADLINE> Latin American Economic News Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, November 24 (Xinhua) -- The following are major
economic news briefs from Latin American countries over the past
few days.
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- Uruguay has shipped 57,766 tons of beef to
neighboring countries so far this year, up 53 percent over the
same period last year.
</P>
<P>
CARACAS -- Direct capital inflow into Venezuela in October
almost tripled that of September, said the Superintendent of
Foreign Investments.
</P>
<P>
Direct investments in October reached 145.95 million dollars,
while some 50.96 million dollars were invested in the country in
September.
</P>
<P>
PANAMA CITY -- A total of 335,376 foreign visitors came to
Panama from January to September this year, an increase of 10
percent compared with the same period in 1996, said the
Panamanian Institute of Tourism.
</P>
<P>
The institute said the increase was due to the holding of a
number of international fairs in the country.
</P>
<P>
The International Airport of Tocumen, the town of Paso Canoa on
the Costa Rican border, and the seaports of Balboa and Cristobal
were the main gateways for tourists.
</P>
<P>
SAN JOSE -- The Central Bank of Costa Rica said the country's
foreign reserves in October dropped by 99.2 million dollars or 9
percent over September, the biggest decrease in the year.
</P>
<P>
Foreign currency reserves were 996.9 million dollars in
October, down from 1.96 billion dollars accumulated a month
earlier.
</P>
<P>
Rodrigo Bolanos, president of the Central Bank, attributed the
decline to the reduction of deposits in dollars from commercial
banks into the Central Bank and to foreign debt duties.
</P>
<P>
MANAGUA -- Inflation during the first 10 months of 1997 in
Nicaragua was 6.2 percent and is expected to rise to 8.2 percent
by the end of the year, the Nicaraguan Central Bank said today.
</P>
<P>
The figure was 10.1 percent in October 1996 and 12.1 percent by
the end of 1996.
</P>
<P>
Economists said inflation was lower after taxes, currency,
salaries and prices were brought under control. 
</P>
</TEXT>
