<HEADLINE> APEC Leaders Urged to Send Right Signals at Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, November 25 (Xinhua) -- Leaders of the Asia Pacific
Economic Cooperation (APEC) are urged to send the right signals at
their summit in Canada and do the right things when they get home,
so as to help restore confidence in the region's economic
development.
</P>
<P>
"Restore confidence is key to recovery and this can only happen
when APEC governments are serious in their undertakings," said the
newspaper The Straits Times in an editorial today. "Revamping the
financial sector will cause pain, but it must take top priority in
the spring-cleaning."
</P>
<P>
It said the current financial crisis plaguing the region's
economies shows that there are serious structural problems,
particularly in the financial sector. However, it also pointed out
that the herd instinct is clearly at work in the currency and
stock markets.
</P>
<P>
"Left unchecked, this negative trend will create even more
problems for the APEC economies which are about to embark on
reforms," the editorial warned.
</P>
<P>
"If market sentiments are to change for the better, APEC
leaders must send the right signals at the summit and do the right
things when they get home," it said.
</P>
<P>
In this regard, the editorial urged the APEC leaders to endorse
a framework plan drafted in Manila last week to promote regional
financial stability.
</P>
<P>
The new draft plan, it said, provides the mechanism for
regional surveillance, better supervision and a cooperative
financing scheme that supplements the resources of the
International Monetary Fund, which should have a pivotal role in
all of this.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the editorial called on the APEC leaders to move
decisively to free up trade and investment.
</P>
<P>
"It will be the wrong thing to do" for the weakened APEC
economies to be tempted to put the brakes on liberalization, it
said.
</P>
<P>
"APEC economies, if they are to do well, must lower the
barriers, and quickly. Open up they must, for competition and
transparency will help foster growth and instill confidence," the
editorial said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
