Viktor Chernomyrdin and his Vietnamese counterpart, Phan Van Khai.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin's three-day visit beginning Monday is the first to
Vietnam by a Russian leader since the disintegration of the Soviet
Union in 1991.
</P>
<P>
In 1994, Vietnam's then-Prime Minister Vo Van Kiet paid an
official visit to Russia.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin and Khai also signed accords on cooperation in oil
and gas exploration, tourism and veterinary sciences.
</P>
<P>
Also topping Chernomyrdin's agenda, however, is Vietnam's
looming debt to Russia.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam owns Russia billions of rubles, but the two sides
cannot agree on what exchange rate should be used for the debt.
</P>
<P>
The Itar-Tass news agency said Russia estimates the debt at
some 17 billion U.S. dollars. When the loans were granted, the
ruble was on a par with the dollar.
</P>
<P>
But at today's rate, the debt would be 1.7 million, says
Vietnam. 
</P>
