<HEADLINE> Australian Fisheries Output Value Up 4 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, November 25 (Xinhua) -- Pearls and rock lobsters
helped push the total value of Australian fisheries production up
about four percent to 1.26 billion U.S. dollars in the last
financial year which ended on June 30, 1997, Australian federal
government's major commodity adviser said today.
</P>
<P>
Stephen Beare, acting executive director of Australian Bureau
of Agricultural and Resource Economics (ABARE), said the rise was
particularly good news following last year's estimated six percent
fall in the gross value of production.
</P>
<P>
"The increase came about mostly as a result of a 39 percent
increase in the gross value of pearl production and a 10 percent
increase in the estimated gross value of rock lobster production,"
Beare said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"Japan continues to be the major market for exports of
Australian fisheries products, accounting for 34 percent," Beare
said.
</P>
<P>
Fisheries product imports, mainly prawns, rose slightly to
about 490 million U.S. dollars in the financial year of 1996-1997.
</P>
<P>
However, despite a two percent drop in the value of exports,
Australia remained a substantial net exporter with 74 percent of
total fisheries production sold overseas, reaping about 910
million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Beare said the value of aquaculture production jumped 14
percent, mainly driven by a sharp rise in the value of pearls.
</P>
</TEXT>
