<HEADLINE> Croatia Asks U.N. Police to Stay On in Eastern Slavonia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZAGREB, November 24 (Xinhua) -- Croatia has invited U.N.
civilian police to stay on in Eastern Slavonia, the last
Serb-controlled part of Croatia, for nine months after the U.N.
administration leaves, Croatian Deputy Foreign Minister Ivo
Sanader today said.
</P>
<P>
The Croatian government also suggested that some 180 U.N.
policemen be stationed as observers in the region.
</P>
<P>
Sanader put forward the suggestion when meeting with
ambassadors of U.N. Security Council members and ambassadors
representing the European Union countries and the Organization for
Security and Cooperation in Europe.
</P>
<P>
The mandate of the current U.N. administration is due to expire
on January 15, after which control of the region should pass to
Croatia in accordance with a 1995 peace accord.
</P>
<P>
Sanader said Foreign Minister Mate Granic had sent a letter to
U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan proposing that U.N. police stay
on for a maximum period of nine months.
</P>
<P>
The deputy foreign minister said the proposal was aimed to
demonstrate Croatia's cooperation with the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
U.S. ambassador Peter Galbraith told reporters after the
meeting that Washington welcomed the proposal. He added that the
task of U.N. police is to ensure local police to do their duty and
protect local residents.
</P>
<P>
Eastern Slavonia, which borders Serbia, was captured by Serbs
in 1991. The Serbs have asked for the U.N. to stay on, fearing
about their future under their former rivals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
