<HEADLINE> OPEC May Lose 600 Billion Dollars due to Carbon Tax </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, November 25 (Xinhua) -- The Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries (OPEC) may lose 600 billion U.S. dollars in
potential revenues by 2020 due to the carbon tax imposed by OECD,
OPEC Secretary General Rilwanu Lukman said.
</P>
<P>
Lukman said at the ASEAN Council on Petroleum (ASCOPE)
Conference and Exhibition '97 here Monday that the carbon tax
imposed in the Organization of Economic Cooperation Development
(OECD) countries would cut worldwide demand for crude oil to
between 85 million and 87 million barrels per day (bpd) by that
year.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN (Association of Southeast Asian Nations) groups Brunei,
Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia, Myanmar, the Philippines, Singapore,
Thailand and Vietnam, whereas OPEC groups Saudi Arab, Kuwait, the
United Arab Emirates, Qatar, Iran, Indonesia, Nigeria, Libya,
Algeria, Iraq and Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
According to an OPEC forecast, the world demand for crude oil
would increase by 37 percent to more than 95 million bpd by 2020
with OPEC accounting for 52 percent of the world's oil market, up
from roughly 40 percent at present.
</P>
<P>
The world demand for crude oil stood at 73.48 million bpd last
year, of which 23.033 million bpd were supplied by OPEC members.
</P>
<P>
The loss in potential revenue would considerably affect OPEC
economies and reduce their capability to expand oil production, he
said.
</P>
<P>
This, in turn, would result in oil supply shortages and price
volatility as OPEC has roughly three-quarters of the world's
proven crude oil reserves, Lukman warned.
</P>
<P>
Lukman arrived here Sunday to attend OPEC's 103rd ministerial
meeting from November 26 to December 1.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
