<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Government Out to Combat Cholera </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, November 25 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lankan President Chandrika
Kumaratunga chaired a meeting Monday in a bid to come up with
measures to check the rapid spread of cholera in the country,
local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, government officials discussed measures to be
taken to deal with the spread of the disease.
</P>
<P>
Measures to be taken include toilet sterilization, chlorinating
wells and food inspection. Doctors and health officials will also
visit houses in the badly-hit areas to help patients.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the country is undertaking a health education
campaign in face of the cholera threat.
</P>
<P>
The Health Ministry has cautioned people not to drink
contaminated water, or eat fruits and vegetables grown at ground
level and fertilized with night soil.
</P>
<P>
Eight deaths have been reported while another 258 people have
been diagnosed as cholera positive since the epidemic broke out in
Chilaw district, north of Colombo, in September.
</P>
<P>
Several other areas were also hit by the epidemic. 
</P>
</TEXT>
