<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese, U.S. Presidents Meet in Vancouver </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VANCOUVER, Canada, November 24 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill
Clinton told Chinese President Jiang Zemin here today that he is
looking forward to visiting China next year.
</P>
<P>
During their 60-minute meeting here, Clinton said that the
U.S. side is very satisfied with the successful state visit by
Jiang to the United States last month.
</P>
<P>
Jiang's visit has improved mutual understanding between the two
countries, he said.
</P>
<P>
This was the 6th meeting between Jiang and Clinton since they
first met in Seattle, the United States, in 1993 at the first APEC
informal leaders' meeting.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said he experienced the friendship as well as willingness
of the American people to develop friendly relations with China.
</P>
<P>
"That is the solid foundation for our two countries to develop
relations," he added.
</P>
<P>
Jiang told Clinton that he is also looking forward to Clinton's
trip to China and expects that the visit will be successful.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, the two leaders also exchanged views on
issues of common concern.
</P>
<P>
Clinton promised to ask Congress to approve as early as
possible the agreement on peaceful use of nuclear energy signed by
the United States and China in 1985 to clear the way for further
bilateral cooperation in this field.
</P>
<P>
Noting the U.S. hope for China's earlier entry into the World
Trade Organization (WTO), Clinton called for speeding up
U.S.-China negotiations on the issue.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said that he would personally see to the progress of
the process of China's admission into the WTO. In reply, Jiang
expressed his appreciation at Clinton's positive attitude on the
issue.
</P>
<P>
Stressing that direct dialogues between leaders can help
improve understanding and narrow differences, Jiang expressed his
willingness to work together with Clinton to broaden common ground
and promote cooperation between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Jiang and Clinton are in Vancouver for the 5th APEC informal
leaders' meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
