<HEADLINE> Hungary, Poland to Cooperate in Joining NATO, EU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUDAPEST, November 24 (Xinhua) -- Hungarian and Polish foreign
ministers agreed here today that their two countries will work
together closely in the course of joining NATO and the European
Union.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a joint press conference with visiting Polish
Foreign Minister Bronislaw Geremek, Hungarian Foreign Minister
Laszlo Kovacs said that relations between the two countries have
developed smoothly, and that Hungary and Poland shared the same
views basically on all issues.
</P>
<P>
Kovacs said Hungary, Poland and the Czech Republic need to
cooperate closely, as the three countries will be granted a
special status in NATO starting January 1998.
</P>
<P>
At a NATO summit in in Madrid in July, Poland, Hungary and the
Czech Republic were invited as the first wave to join the alliance
by 1999.
</P>
<P>
Kovacs said the foreign ministers of the three countries will
visit the United States together next year to talk with U.S.
senators on NATO's eastward expansion.
</P>
<P>
Geremek arrived here earlier today and met with Hungarian
President Goncz Arpad, Prime Minister Horn Gyula and National
Assembly President Gal Zoltan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
