<DOCNO> XIE19971125.0269 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Matured Debts of Indonesian Private Businesses Reach </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, November 25 (Xinhua) -- Bank Indonesia revealed that
at least 9.6 billion U.S. dollars of the 65 billion dollars in the
private sector's foreign debts would mature by March 1998.
</P>
<P>
At a hearing with the House of Representatives here Monday,
Bank Indonesia Governor Soedradjad Djiwandono said the amount
covered principals and interest charges.
</P>
<P>
He reaffirmed that total private foreign debts as of September
totaled 65 billion dollars. The private debts were also part of
Indonesia's total debts which amounted to 117.3 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
"However, the concern in the market is how much of the debts
are short-term, and more importantly, how much of them will mature
soon," Soedradjad said.
</P>
<P>
The central bank governor reiterated that the government, with
the help of the International Monetary Fund (IMF), would continue
to ensure enough supply of dollars on the domestic market.
</P>
<P>
The IMF has arranged a 23 billion U.S. dollar financial package
for Indonesia to support its economic reforms to survive the
current currency turmoil plaguing the region.
</P>
<P>
Soedradjad also called on the public to remain calm, asking for
their patience with and support to the government efforts to
stabilize the national currency rupiah and revive the economy.
</P>
<P>
The value of the rupiah has dropped by about 50 percent against
the U.S. dollar this year following the monetary crisis in the
Southeast Asian region.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian government introduced monetary and fiscal
policies, trade deregulation and structural adjustments to
overcome the crisis. The government has also cut development
budget, rescheduled major projects and closed 16 insolvent private
banks.
</P>
<P>
"These programs are badly needed to restore our economy, which
is weakened by monetary turmoil in Asia and facing hard challenge
from the internationally integrated financial market," he noted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
