<DOCNO> XIE19971125.0270 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Urges Manila to Stop Intervention on Foreign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, November 25 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary Fund
(IMF) has urged the Philippine Central Bank to stop intervention
on the spot foreign exchange market for lack of proof that the
local currency was in fact undervalued.
</P>
<P>
"There is no strong evidence that the peso is undervalued," the
IMF mission which came to the Philippines last week to review the
country's economic performance said in its concluding report.
</P>
<P>
The IMF instead recommended that the central monetary authority
should allow the "peso to seek its own level" rather than risk
exhaustion of the country's foreign reserves, local press today
quoted the report as saying.
</P>
<P>
"It would be imprudent for the central bank to intervene, given
the relatively low level of foreign reserves," the IMF report
stressed.
</P>
<P>
The country's gross international reserves had dwindled to 10.2
billion U.S. dollars by the end of October from a high of 12.25
billion dollars in the first quarter of the year.
</P>
<P>
The central bank sold more than 2 billion dollars to fend off
speculative attacks on the peso following a regionwide currency
turmoil sparked by the freefall of the Thai baht in early July.
</P>
<P>
The local currency already depreciated by more than 30 percent
from the level before the de facto devaluation in early July
despite the central bank's wasted effort to prop up the peso.
</P>
</TEXT>
