<DOCNO> XIE19971125.0272 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Export Growth Predicted at 10 Percent This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, November 25 (Xinhua) -- Thai exports are likely to
grow by some ten percent this year in baht value due to the baht
depreciation, Thai commerce officials predicted.
</P>
<P>
The Thai export growth prediction would be lower in baht value
if the baht had not depreciated sharply since July 2 this year,
the officials said at a meeting here with local exporters Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Commerce Ministry reportedly had postponed its issuing of
1998 forecast due to the volatility of foreign exchange rates, the
officials said. The government will wait and see how weak the baht
would be at the end of this year and then decide the real export
growth for this year before making forecasts for the next year.
</P>
<P>
They also said that the government is considering setting two
export targets for the next year, one in baht value and the other
in U.S. dollar value in view of the baht volatility.
</P>
<P>
Thai exports totaled 1,205.3 billion baht during the first nine
months of this year, up nearly 15 percent year-on-year, while Thai
imports for the period posted 1,398.4 billion baht, driving the
country's trade deficit lower to 193.1 billion, down 13.6 percent
compared with the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
Major Thai export goods were computers and computer parts,
garments, integrated circuits, rice and frozen shrimp, which
accounted for 27 percent of the total during the period.
</P>
<P>
Major Thai imports during the period were vehicles and parts,
transformers, motors, chemical products, and plastic resin, which
accounted for 63 percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
The officials predicted that the surplus would continue for the
last quarter of this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
