<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0130 GMT, November 25 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI -- The current political crisis in India triggered by
the release of an investigative report on the assassination of
former prime minister Rajiv Gandhi deepened Monday as the ruling
United Front refused to punish one of its constituents allegedly
linked to the killing.
</P>
<P>
The so-called Jain Commission report, tabled in the parliament
on November 20, has indicted the Dravida Munnetra Kazagham (DMK),
a major constituent of the United Front, in the assassination of
Rajiv Gandhi in 1991. (India-Political Crisis)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkish police and gendarme soldiers seized 165
kilograms of hashish in a recent operation in eastern Turkey, the
semi-official Anatolia News Agency reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The agency quoted a statement issued by the office of Bitlis
governor as saying that the gendarme soldiers disguised as drug
buyers bargained with drug smuggler Felemez Aslan in Mutki town of
Bitlis province. However, Aslan found the drug buyers as
government troops and managed to flee in the dark.
(Turkey-Hashish)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
KIEV -- Ukraine is considering repairing the ill-fated
Chernobyl nuclear power plant as it collected enough money at a
recent fund-raising conference, Ukrainian President Leonid Kuchma
has said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference here, Kuchma said Ukraine would
invest the funds into building a new shelter over the No. 4
reactor.
</P>
<P>
Blown up in 1986, sending radioactive cloud over a large part
of Europe, the reactor fell out to be the worst nuclear accident
in history. (Ukraine-Chernobyl-Nuclear Plant)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- Iraq on Monday denied U.S. Defense Secretary William
Cohen's allegation that Iraqi authorities had obstructed U.N.
inspectors' access to suspected sites in Iraq, the official Iraqi
News Agency (INA) reported.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted an official spokesman as saying that Cohen's
statement was meant to mislead the world public opinion in
preparation for straining Iraq's relationship with the U.N.
Special Commission (UNSCOM) in charge of dismantling Iraqi weapons
of mass destruction. (Iraq-U.S.-Allegation)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- The global drugs market continued to be dominated by
the U.S. market in September, with U.S. year-on-year growth rising
to 15 percent compared with a seven percent average growth of the
world's 10 largest markets.
</P>
<P>
Citing figures released Monday by IMS International, a
specialist provider of healthcare information, the Financial Times
newspaper reported today that pharmaceuticals sales in 10 of the
largest national markets rose to 167.4 billion U.S. dollars for
the year to September. (World-Drugs Sales)
</P>
<P>
