<DOCNO> XIE19971125.0281 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Full Text of Jiang's Speech at APEC CEO Summit (Part I) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VANCOUVER, Canada, November 24 (Xinhua) -- Following is the
full text of a speech by Chinese President Jiang Zemin at the
special extended session of the APEC CEO Summit, entitled "Towards
Broader Cooperation Among Enterprises in Asia-Pacific", here today.

Mr. Chair,
Ladies and Gentlemen,
</P>
<P>
I wish to thank Prime Minister Jean Chretien for his kind
invitation which gives me an opportunity to attend today's meeting
and share my views with you on strengthened cooperation among
Asia-Pacific enterprises.
</P>
<P>
With the advent of a new century, mankind is now at an
important historical juncture. The 20th century has witnessed
tremendous economic and social progress, and the 21st century will
be full of opportunities and challenges. All of us share a
responsibility to bring a hopeful Asia-Pacific into the new
century.
</P>
<P>
An important task for APEC now is to push forward progressively
and continuously economic and technical cooperation (Ecotech)
within the region and promote a mutually reinforcing relationship
between Ecotech and trade and investment liberalization with a
view to achieving the common development and prosperity of all
countries and regions in the Asia-Pacific. China stands ready to
make positive contributions to this end.
</P>
<P>
At the 1996 APEC Informal Leadership Meeting, I made a proposal
to establish an APEC-wide network of science and technology
industrial parks to facilitate the sharing of experiences and
information exchanges in the region. China has since opened four
national level parks of this kind to APEC members together with
the Beijing environmental protection center equipped with advanced
facilities. All this shows the positive attitude that China has
adopted toward closer Ecotech in the region.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971125.0282 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Full Text of Jiang's Speech at APEC CEO Summit (Part II) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Modern enterprises are an important force in propelling
economic growth and scientific research and development.
Strengthened cooperation among enterprises is an important
foundation for enhanced Ecotech within APEC.
</P>
<P>
Strengthened cooperation among enterprises in the Asia-Pacific
should follow a number of basic principles. First, a new
cooperation mechanism for the purpose of common development of
enterprises in the region should be established. It should be
based on mutual respect, cooperation on an equal footing and
mutual benefit while allowing diversity and flexibility and
sticking to dialogues and consultations. Second, different needs
of enterprises of various countries and regions should be taken
into proper consideration and their interest relations handled in
a fair and reasonable manner. Third, policies of encouraging
greater Ecotech among enterprises should be formulated and steps
taken to remove all man-made restrictive and discriminatory
measures. It can be expected that with continued efforts in
practice, Ecotech among Asia-Pacific enterprises will surely
become more extensive.
</P>
<P>
Since adopting the policy of reform and opening-up toward the
end of 1970s, China has maintained the momentum of a sustained and
rapid economic growth. The average annual growth rate is around
9.8 percent. While doing that, we have managed to bring inflation
under effective control. Right now, China enjoys political
stability, economic prosperity, ethnic harmony and social progress
and our people are living and working in peace and contentment.
</P>
<P>
China's economic achievement has injected vigor into the
economic development of the Asia-Pacific and contributed to
regional stability.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971125.0283 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southwestern Chinese Province To Help Large Enterprises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, November 25 (Xinhua) -- The government of southwest
China's Yunnan Province has decided to support 40 large
enterprises and groups as part of its efforts to create 100 large
businesses by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
At least one of the 100 will have annual sales of 10 billion
yuan, and three will have annual sales between 5 and 10 billion
yuan each.
</P>
<P>
According to Li Jiating, Yunnan's vice-governor in charge of
industry, finance and trade, 31 of the 40 businesses are
industrial enterprises that account for 65 percent of the
province's industrial sales and 90 percent of the pre-tax profits.
</P>
<P>
The success of these enterprises will help the overall economic
development of Yunnan, Li said, but they need to expand at low
cost, lower assets-to-liabilities ratio, and with better
management.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971125.0284 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Full Text of Jiang's Speech at APEC CEO Summit (Part III) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Not long ago, the Communist Party of China convened its 15th
National Congress which vowed to carry forward the cause of
building socialism with Chinese characteristics pioneered by
Mr. Deng Xiaoping. The Congress laid down a master plan for the
cross-century development of China's reform, opening up and
modernization drive. Our objectives are: to double our 2000 GNP by
the year 2010 while ensuring a more comfortable life for the
people and putting in place a relatively full-fledged socialist
market economic structure; to further develop our national economy
and improve our various institutions with another 10 years of
efforts; and to realize modernization by and large and turn China
into a prosperous, strong, democratic and culturally advanced
socialist country by the middle of the next century.
</P>
<P>
The parallel development of various economic sectors with
public ownership playing a dominant role is the basic economic
system of China at the current stage. Among 8 million-plus
enterprises under various forms of economic ownership in China,
300,000 are state-owned. To rejuvenate them, we are quickening the
tempo of reform by employing all operational and organizational
methods that reflect the laws of socialized production, including
the joint stock system and joint stock partnership, and
establishing a modern enterprise system so as to give better play
to their dominant role in the economy. In addition, we are
promoting technological upgrading of the enterprises by
encouraging and guiding greater investment by enterprises and
society into technological overhaul of existing enterprises and
developing a market-oriented mechanism of new product development
and technical innovation. As for the host of difficulties and
problems we have encountered in the reform process, we are taking
vigorous steps to solve them. We are confident that under the
guidance of the sound theory and with the rich experience we have
gained in reform and thanks to the method of piloting before
popularization and the concerted efforts of all our employees, the
reform of our state-owned enterprises will surely attain its
anticipated success.
</P>
<P>
To upgrade the technology, equipment and innovation capability
of enterprises is very important for them to become more vigorous
and acquire a new mode of growth. China has introduced a project
aimed at prodding enterprises to set up an innovation system with
technology center as the focal point.
</P>
<P>
Opening to the outside world is a long-term, basic state policy
of China. We are endeavoring to improve our all-dimensional,
multi-levelled and wide ranging pattern of openness, further
develop an open economy and take a more active approach towards
international economic and technical cooperation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971125.0285 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Full Text of Jiang's Speech at APEC CEO Summit (Part IV) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
China will continue to steadily open its market, speed up the
opening of its energy, communications and other infrastructure
industries and gradually open its service industries such as
banking and insurance. Efforts will be made to further improve
our foreign-related legal regimes, protect intellectual property
rights, improve trade and investment climate, protect the rights
and interests of foreign-funded enterprises according to law and
introduce national treatment so as to create a level playing
ground of competition for both Chinese and foreign enterprises.
Import of equipment for foreign-funded projects that tally with
China's industrial policy and can bring in new technologies will
benefit from renewed necessary preferential policies.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to rapid economic development, China has been
transformed from a seller's market to a buyer's one. For foreign
enterprises desiring to enter the China market or enhance their
market competitiveness, a financial advantage alone is not
enough. More importantly, they should back themselves with
advanced technologies and products with greater technological
contents. In the socialist market economy we are building in
China, prices of an overwhelming majority of commodities are
determined by the marketplace. This, if I may, is the important
economic information I wish to bring you today.
</P>
<P>
What you are representing here are some of the most powerful
enterprises in the Asia-Pacific and even in the world. I welcome
your broader cooperation with China in the area of new
technologies, new techniques, new equipment and advanced
management expertise, especially in the fields of high-tech
industries, infrastructure development, environmental protection
and development of human resources. This will bring benefit to all.
</P>
<P>
Let us set our eyes on the future, seize the opportunity and
work together so as to make fresh contributions to the economic
development and prosperity in the Asia-Pacific.
</P>
<P>
Thank you. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
