<DOCNO> XIE19971125.0286 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Senator Praises Construction of Three Gorges Dam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 24 (Xinhua) -- A U.S. Republican senator
today praised the construction of the Three Gorges Dam in China
for its benefit to the people and criticized the U.S. Ex-Im Bank
for not supporting U.S. firms in investing in the largest-ever
dam project in the world.
</P>
<P>
Frank Murkowski, who recently took a trip with another senator
to China, told reporters here that it was "unfortunate" that the
Ex-Im Bank stuck to the policy of not granting guaranteed loans to
U.S. firms, which were interested in the project.
</P>
<P>
Murkowski strongly refuted the Ex-Im Bank's inference that the
building of the dam would lead to environmental damage along the
Yangtze River, saying that what will happen after the completion
of the dam will be just the contrary.
</P>
<P>
"The Three Gorges Dam will generate about 18,000 megawatts,
which is equal to about 36,500 megawatt coal-fired plants," he
said. That is a great "contribution to air quality."
</P>
<P>
One of other contributions by the dam will be the benefit to
navigation, Murkowski said. "It will increase navigation, which
will provide larger vessels to have access on the Yangtze River
further up to Chongqing," the largest city in southwestern China.
</P>
<P>
The senator also refuted criticism that the building of the dam
will leave 1.7 million people displaced, saying 70 million people
were constantly displaced by the floods that occurred from time to
time.
</P>
<P>
"Those floods won't occur anymore," because of the dam, which
will be able to control the water flow, he added.
</P>
<P>
During his stay in China, Murkowski talked with President Jiang
Zemin for about one hour. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971125.0287 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese College Students Visit Drug Rehabilitation Center </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 25 (Xinhua) -- Twenty Chinese college
students visited a drug rehabilitation center in Beijing on
Monday to see the effects of drugs, today's China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
The students were allowed to see the addicts' living
conditions, watch them exercise and talk with them, their
relatives and doctors.
</P>
<P>
"I am deeply impressed by them," said a student from China
University of Politics and Law.
</P>
<P>
It was part of the university's education activities examing
the topic of "drugs".
</P>
<P>
The addicts, trying to break free from narcotics, usually stay
in the center for three months.
</P>
<P>
The students had numerous questions -- why the addicts began
using drugs, where they worked before becoming addicts and what
their future goals are.
</P>
<P>
"Most of the addicts are as young as the visiting students,"
the paper quoted Chu Zhiyong, a teacher and program initiator, as
saying. "I hope the students can learn the harm of drug abuse".
</P>
<P>
The university's drug-education activities are in accord with a
circular released early this month by China's National
Narcotics Control Committee and the State Education Commission
(SEC).
</P>
<P>
The circular calls on students -- in universities and primary
and middle schools -- to participate in drug prevention education
programs.
</P>
<P>
The education program, known as "Cherish Your Life and Keep Far
Away From the Drugs," is aimed toward youth.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971125.0288 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar Calls for Better Bank Services to Customers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, November 25 (Xinhua) -- A senior Myanmar finance
official has called for giving better services to the customers,
stressing the importance of banks' role in the country's economic
progress and public confidence in banks.
</P>
<P>
While meeting with officials of state-owned banks here Monday,
Minister for Finance and Revenue Brigadier General Win Tin called
for improving dealing with the public and avoiding delay in
depositing and drawing.
</P>
<P>
The minister also urged bank staffs to keep money safe and
avoid malpractice and bad dealing with customers, citing some
complaints by the public about cases at some state-owned banks,
official newspaper The New Light of Myanmar reported today.
</P>
<P>
Win Tin warned that severe action will be taken against those
who are responsible for bad practices.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, there are six state-run banks
in Myanmar, and 25 private banks have been added since the country
reformed its financial management system in line with the
market-oriented economy introduced in the late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
A total of 48 representative offices of foreign banks have been
set up in the country, and some of them plan to establish joint
ventures with local banks in light of Myanmar's entry into the
second phase of its financial reform.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
