<DOCNO> XIE19971125.0291 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Central Bank to Monitor Currency Swaps </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, November 25 (Xinhua) -- The Central Bank of the
Philippines will regulate banks' swap transactions, particularly
those involving the conversion of peso placements into foreign
currency deposits.
</P>
<P>
Alberto Reyes, deputy governor of the central bank, said here
Monday that his bank is working closely with the Bankers
Association of the Philippines to draft rules and regulations on
so-called "engineered swaps".
</P>
<P>
Reyes said that the central bank is studying the possibility of
imposing a ceiling on swap transactions to discourage banks from
using this scheme in skirting central bank rules.
</P>
<P>
The rules could be worked out by the first quarter of 1998, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Swaps are agreements between two parties to swap debts so that
one meets the interest and capital payments of the other.
</P>
<P>
But engineered swaps basically involves conversion of peso
deposits into dollars and then back to pesos.
</P>
<P>
Reyes said that banks engaged in engineered swaps are able to
avoid complying with the liquidity reserve requirements imposed by
the central bank.
</P>
<P>
They also avoid paying tax by entering into engineered swap
deals, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971125.0292 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Scientists Issuing SOS for South China Tigers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 25 (Xinhua) -- The South China tiger, a major
attraction in local zoos, could become extinct within 30 to 50
years if it does not receive adequate protection, the "China
Daily" reported today.
</P>
<P>
Apart from those held in zoos, field surveys in the 1980s
showed that there are 20 to 30 South China tigers in Fujian,
Guangdong, Jiangxi provinces and the Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous
Region, the tigers's original habitat.
</P>
<P>
There are only five of them left in Guangdong Province, where
forest is being destroyed as a result of the fast industrial
growth, said Wang Menghu, executive deputy secretary-general of
the China Zoo Association (CZA).
</P>
<P>
The surveys discovered only some tiger tracks, excrement and
traces of urine.
</P>
<P>
"It is possible that people will no longer be able to see these
tigers in the not too distant future unless effective and concrete
measures are taken to save and protect this rare and precious
animal," the zoological expert warned.
</P>
<P>
The life span of South China tigers is 20 to 25 years. But the
tigers breed infrequently, and the survival rate of infant tigers
is low due to increasing inbreeding.
</P>
<P>
Wang attributed the reduced number of the tigers to the serious
destruction of forest as a result of rapid industrial growth and
tourism development.
</P>
<P>
To save and protect the south China tiger, Wang said the CZA
has established an information data bank, a gene bank and several
scientific research projects.
</P>
<P>
"In addition to trying to save and protect tigers in the wild,
we have to improve the breeding and rearing of future generations
of tigers in zoos, making use of such techniques as blood testing
and gene research," Wang said.
</P>
<P>
With hard work and the help of artificial insemination it is
expected that the number of South China tigers will reach 150 to 180
in the coming century, Wang said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971125.0293 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Accepts IMF Arrangement for Exit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, November 25 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government has
agreed to the suggestion of the International Monetary Fund (IMF)
for a "precautionary arrangement" as the country exits from IMF
supervision by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
Philippine President Fidel Ramos accepted the offer of IMF
Managing Director Michel Camdessus when they met in Manila last
week because of the uncertainties brought by the financial crisis
in the East Asian region, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
"We exit but because of this turmoil in the Asia Pacific, it
has been -- and we have accepted it -- that a precautionary
arrangement be put in place for us in a form of a special
program," Ramos said in an interview with the Washington Post
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The offer of the IMF, he said, will be necessary to safeguard
the economic growth gained by the country for the past five years
as well as prevent it from severe damage brought by the
speculative attacks on the peso.
</P>
<P>
He said the precautionary arrangement with the IMF does not
necessary mean standby fund but sharing of information, analysis
and recommendations.
</P>
<P>
The IMF's proposal will also complement the four measures
adopted by the finance ministers from the Asia Pacific at their
conference in Manila last week, he said.
</P>
<P>
The measures include a monitoring system to watch the latest
development in the region, a monetary mechanism under the auspices
of the IMF to serve as a quick response fund for economies in
distress, closer cooperation on financial matters and individual
internal reforms to be undertaken by the economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
