<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Environmentally-Friendly Buses Run in Chinese City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, November 25 (Xinhua) -- Environmentally-friendly buses
have made their first appearance on the streets of Haikou, the
capital of China's southernmost island province of Hainan.
</P>
<P>
The 35 new buses run on liquefied petroleum gas (LPG) instead
of petroleum, thus reducing the amount of pollutant by 80 percent and
the cost of fuel by 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
Haikou plans to spend about 30 million yuan (about 3.6 million
US dollars) on transforming 5,400 automobiles into "green buses" and
building 18 LPG stations.
</P>
<P>
The 35 new buses are all Chinese-made with advanced
technology. Officials say that LPG will be used on all buses and
most cabs in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Environmental protection departments report that pollution in
many big cities in China is mainly caused by car and truck exhaust
rather than by coal.
</P>
<P>
Green automobiles are expected to change this serious
situation and help protect the environment. Two other south China
cities, Shenzhen and Guangzhou, already have some similar buses
operating on their streets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
