<HEADLINE> McRae and Burns Take Joint Lead in RAC Rally </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, November 24 (Xinhua) -- British drivers Colin McRae and
Richard Burns shared the leading place of the British RAC Rally
after the second day race on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Burns seized the lead in his Mitsubishi on the day's first
stage in Wales when overnight leader McRae ran off the road into a
ditch in heavy fog and dropped to eighth.
</P>
<P>
But Burns's choice of tyres on the central Wales gravel stages
proved poor. He lost time as McRae recovered through the day and
was hit with a 10-second penalty after leaving the 16th stage late
because of a suspension problem.
</P>
<P>
McRae's championship rival Tommi Makinen had a frustrating day
that saw him up to fourth place after the day's opening stage
before he slowly dropped back after a 120 mph spin and a
transmission problem.
</P>
<P>
The Swede, who has a heavy cold, ended the day in the sixth
spot he needs to clinch the title having been handed a 20-second
penalty for leaving the service point after stage 16 late when
mechanics replaced an output flange.
</P>
<P>
His target of sixth place looked more attainable after
then-sixth Frenchman Didier Auriol rolled out of the rally after
a mistake on the 17th stage.
</P>
<P>
McRae set the fastest time in his Subaru on five of the day's
seven stages to climb up the order after his early incident and is
within reach of the win he needs to stand a chance of taking the
championship.
</P>
<P>
Finn Juha Kankkunen ended the day in third place, but his Ford
team-mate Carlos Sainz lost time on the 18th stage after suffering
a driveshaft problem and ended the day fourth.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday's final leg has more stages in southern Wales before
the finish in Cheltenham and McRae will start first because he set
the fastest time on the opening stage of the rally. 
</P>
</TEXT>
