<DOCNO> XIE19971125.0307 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Economy Forecast for Moderate Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, November 24 (Xinhua) -- Despite the possible impact
of some negative factors such as the financial turbulence in
Southeast Asia and a trend of growing trade deficit, economists
see the United States to maintain moderate economic growth and low
inflation in the next few years.
</P>
<P>
The economy is expected to grow by an average annual rate
between 2 percent and 2.6 percent this year and next, with
inflation below 3 percent, the Journal of Commerce reported today,
quoting a report of the Commerce Department as saying.
</P>
<P>
The report, jointly conducted with a private company
DRI/McGraw-Hill, considered higher foreign trade deficit the
principal drag on the economy next year.
</P>
<P>
However, chief economist of DRI/McGraw-Hill David Wyss said the
moderate growth may continue in the next five years, making it the
longest economic expansion since World War II.
</P>
<P>
Possible reduction of U.S. exports of such items as computer
equipment and aircraft to Southeast Asia may cost U.S. output a
minor dip of about one-fourth of a percentage point, Wyss said.
</P>
<P>
Another group of 39 professional forecasters see the economy to
grow at a moderate pace at least through the year 2003.
</P>
<P>
The forecasters, belonging to the Federal Reserve Bank of
Philadelphia, pegged U.S. real GDP growth at 2.7 percent in the
fourth quarter of this year and 3.7 percent for 1997.
</P>
<P>
Growth will decelerate gradually over the next five quarters
to 2.2 percent in the fourth quarter of 1998, they said in a
survey released today.
</P>
<P>
They anticipate the inflation, measured by the Consumer Price
Index, to average 2.5 percent for the fourth quarter, 2 percent
for 1997 and 2.6 percent for 1998.
</P>
<P>
The government reported last week that the CPI rose 1.8 percent
at a seasonally adjusted annual rate in the first 10 months of
this year, against a 3.3 percent jump for 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971125.0308 </DOCNO>
