<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IFC Issues Lira Callable Bond </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 24 (Xinhua) -- The International Finance
Corporation (IFC) today announced the launching of an Italian lira
denominated callable bond under its global medium term note
program.
</P>
<P>
The bond carries a coupon of 14 percent per annum in the first
year, and thereafter a coupon of 16 percent less two times the
12-month Libor. The bond has a final maturity of 10 years and has
been issued to investors at par. The issue is listed on the
Luxembourg stock exchange, and is swapped into floating rate U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
This transaction brings the IFC's market borrowing to about
1,595 million dollars for the fiscal year 1998 which began on July
1, 1997.
</P>
<P>
The IFC is a member of the World Bank Group and the largest
source of financing for private projects in developing countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
