<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Plunges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, November 24 (Xinhua) -- New York stocks pulled back
sharply today amid fears that the shut-down of a major Japanese
brokerage will affect the Tokyo Stock Exchange, which was closed
for a holiday.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average plunged 113.15 points to
7,767.92.
</P>
<P>
Declining issues outnumbered advancers by nearly a 3-to-1
margin on the New York Stock Exchange, where volume totaled 513.98
million shares as against 592.04 million in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock list fell 16.42 at 946.67, and
the NYSE composite index fell 7.71 at 495.14.
</P>
<P>
The Nasdaq composite index fell 33.76 to 1,586.99, and the
American Stock Exchange composite index fell 9.63 to 663.51.
</P>
<P>
Yamaichi, Japan's No.4 securities firm, officially announced
today it was shutting down. It suffered debts amounting to 24
billion U.S. dollars and was beset by a payoff scandal. The news
shook the resilience of the U.S. stock market to overseas market
dropping last week.
</P>
<P>
European markets also fell today with the Tokyo stock market
closing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
