<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Prospects of Sino-British Relationship Look Better </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, November 24 (Xinhua) - Derek Fatchett, Minister of
State for Foreign Affairs, said today that Britain and China now
enjoy "a unique opportunity" to move ahead in their bilateral
relationship.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a conference "China And Britain - Partners For The
21st Century", Fatchett said that after the smooth handover of
Hong Kong, the prospects of Sino-British relationship "look better
than ever".
</P>
<P>
Why is that? Fatchett said: "I believe we have a solid basis to
build on... The successful handover of Hong Kong is a model of
what we can achieve together through trust and cooperation."
</P>
<P>
On how to further develop bilateral relations, the Minister
said: "We are also working to build a new level of cooperation
between Britain and China on global issues, such as
non-proliferation of weapons and the environment."
</P>
<P>
"No one could dispute China's key place in the world. So there
is great scope for us to work together, for example by deepening
cooperation as fellow Permanent Members of the UN Security
Council," he added.
</P>
<P>
Referring to China's accession to the WTO, Fatchett said that
with its EU partners, Britain is keen to bring China into the WTO,
assuming that China's membership can be negotiated on mutually
satisfactory terms.
</P>
<P>
He said: "China's membership of the WTO on the right terms,
will carry important benefits for China's own development, as well
as for her trading partners and for the global trading system as a
whole."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
