<DOCNO> XIE19971125.0315 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jiang on Principles for Cooperation Among APEC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VANCOUVER, Canada, November 24 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President
Jiang Zemin today outlined three basic principles for cooperation
among enterprises in the Asia-Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the APEC CEO Summit, a gathering of about 300
corporate elite of the Asia-Pacific region, Jiang said modern
enterprises are an important force in propelling economic growth
and scientific research and development.
</P>
<P>
"Strengthened cooperation among enterprises is an important
foundation for enhanced Ecotech (economic and technical
cooperation) within APEC," Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
He said the strengthened cooperation should follow the
following three basic principles:
</P>
<P>
First, a new cooperation mechanism for the purpose of common
development of enterprises in the region should be established. It
should be based on mutual respect, cooperation on an equal footing
and mutual benefit while allowing diversity and flexibility and
sticking to dialogues and consultations.
</P>
<P>
Second, different needs of enterprises of various countries and
regions should be taken into proper consideration and their
interest relations handled in a fair and reasonable manner.
</P>
<P>
Third, policies of encouraging greater Ecotech among
enterprises should be formulated and steps taken to remove all
man-made restrictive and discriminatory measures.
</P>
<P>
"It can be expected that with continued efforts in practice,
Ecotech among Asia-Pacific enterprises will surely become more
extensive," the Chinese president said.
</P>
<P>
He believed that an important task for APEC now is to push
forward progressively and continuously economic and technical
cooperation within the region and promote a mutually reinforcing
relationship between Ecotech and trade and investment
liberalization.
</P>
<P>
"China stands ready to make positive contributions to this
end," he said.
</P>
<P>
Jiang told the chief executive officers that he made a proposal
at last year's APEC informal leadership meeting to establish an
APEC-wide network of science and technology industrial parks to
facilitate the sharing of experiences and information exchanges in
the region.
</P>
<P>
China has since opened four national level parks of this kind
to APEC members together with the Beijing environmental protection
center equipped with advanced facilities, Jiang noted.
</P>
<P>
"All this shows the positive attitude that China has adopted
toward closer Ecotech in the region," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971125.0316 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Civil Rights Fighting Internet Hate Speech </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 24 (Xinhua) -- The largest civil rights
coalition of the United States and a regional Bell telephone
company have created a Web site designed to fight Internet hate
speech.
</P>
<P>
The Leadership Conference on Civil Rights said today the site
-- www.civilrights.org -- will be maintained for two years with a
contribution from Bell Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton made a call two weeks ago at a
White House Conference on Hate Crimes to find ways to fight the
problem.
</P>
<P>
"You are providing an antidote to cyberhate," Clinton told the
civil rights coalition in a letter read by Transportation
Secretary Rodney Slater at a news conference today.
</P>
<P>
Wade Henderson, LCCR executive director, said the idea to
create a Web site was triggered by a proliferation of Internet
hate speech by groups such as the Ku Klux Klan and White Aryan
Resistance.
</P>
<P>
Bell Atlantic chairman Ray Smith cited a study by the
Anti-Defamation League showing the number of hate sites on the
Internet has doubled to 250 in the past year.
</P>
<P>
Calling the new site "an antidote for poison," he said the idea
is to "counter the frightening espousal of hatred and violence
against Americans because of their race, gender, religious or
sexual orientation," he said.
</P>
<P>
Henderson said hate groups have become more sophisticated in
communicating their doctrines and recruiting. "Instead of the
street, they recruit on the net," he said.
</P>
<P>
In addition to providing information on hate crimes around the
country, the site will explain various strategies to address those
crimes and offer materials for young people, parents and teachers
to encourage diversity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971125.0317 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U-2 Takes Third Flights over Iraq without Incident </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 24 (Xinhua) -- A U-2 spy plane flew over
central Iraq without incident to take pictures of sites for the
U.N. weapons inspection mission, U.S. State Department said on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
"There was a U-2 flight today that took photographs of
weapons of mass destruction-related facilities," spokesman James
Foley said at a briefing.
</P>
<P>
It was the third time flight by U-2 planes within two weeks
since the outbreak of a weapons inspection dispute between the
United States and Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The United States has said it will continue to keep vigilant
on Iraq despite its agreement to let U.N. weapons inspection
teams back on their work.
</P>
<P>
U.S. warplanes and warships, reinforced to the Gulf after the
crisis over weapons inspections occurred on Oct. 29, will stay in
the region and sanctions on Iraq will not be lifted until
Baghdad subjects itself to full compliance with U.N.
resolutions, U.S. officials said.
</P>
<P>
"We're still in a watching mode. We don't consider that the
issue is closed. The teams have returned, they've started their
work and let's see whether they're able now to work more
effectively," Foley said.
</P>
<P>
A new dispute erupted as the U.N. weapons inspectors, who
returned to Iraq last Friday, insisted to check some sites that
the Iraqi authority claimed belonged to presidential area and
would not be allowed to enter as sensitive areas.
</P>
<P>
Foley said Iraq had no right to limit the scope of
inspections. "No sites is to be off limits to UNSCOM (U.N.
Special commission) in the performance of its mission," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
